    {"back": "<b>Answer: B) 0.21</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>Let M = event that customer insures more than one car and S = event that customer insurers a<br>sports car. Then applying DeMorgan\u2019s Law, compute the desired probability as:<br>( ) ( ) ( ) ( ) ( ) ( )<br>( ) ( ) ( ) ( ) ( )( )<br>Pr Pr 1 Pr 1 Pr Pr Pr<br>1 Pr Pr Pr Pr 1 0.70 0.20 0.15 0.70 0.205<br>cccM S MS MS M S MS<br>M S SM M<br>\uf8ee\uf8f9\u2229 = \u222a = \u2212\u222a = \u2212 +\u2212\u2229 \uf8ee\uf8f9\uf8f0\uf8fb\uf8f0\uf8fb<br>= \u2212 \u2212 + = \u2212\u2212+ =<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q9. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "An insurance company examines its pool of auto insurance customers and gathers the<br>following information:<br><br>(i) All customers insure at least one car.<br>(ii) 70% of the customers insure more than one car.<br>(iii) 20% of the customers insure a sports car.<br>(iv) Of those customers who insure more than one car, 15% insure a sports car.<br><br>Calculate the probability that a randomly selected customer insures exactly one car and<br>that car is not a sports car.<br><br>A) 0.13<br>B) 0.21<br>C) 0.24<br>D) 0.25<br>E) 0.30", "tags": ["ExamP::GeneralProbability"]},
