    {"back": "<b>Answer: E) /4ln0.3 (0.3)4<br>x\u2212</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>The cumulative distribution function for the exponential distribution of the lifespan is<br>() 1 xFx e \u03bb\u2212= \u2212 , for positive x.<br>The probability that the lifespan exceeds 4 years is 40.3 1 (4)Fe \u03bb\u2212= \u2212= . Thus (ln0.3)/4\u03bb =\u2212 .<br>For positive x, the probability density function is<br>(ln 0.3) x/4 /4ln 0.3 ln 0.3( ) e (0.3) .4 4<br>xxfx e \u03bb\u03bb \u2212= = \u2212= \u2212<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q142. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "The lifespan, in years, of a certain computer is exponentially distributed. The probability<br>that its lifespan exceeds four years is 0.30.<br><br>Let f(x) represent the density function of the computer\u2019s lifespan, in years, for x &gt; 0.<br><br>Determine which of the following is an expression for f(x).<br><br>A) /41 (0.3) x\u2212\u2212<br>B) /41 (0.7) x\u2212<br>C) /41 (0.3) x\u2212<br>D) /4ln0.7 (0.7)4<br>x\u2212<br>E) /4ln0.3 (0.3)4<br>x\u2212", "tags": ["ExamP::UnivariateRV", "ExamP::UnivariateRV::ContinuousDistributions"]},
    {"back": "<b>Answer: C) 1.26</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>It is not necessary to determine the constant of proportionality. Let it be c. To determine the<br>mode, set the derivative of the density function equal to zero and solve.<br>2 31 31 2 32 2<br>3 4 32<br>44 4<br>3 1/3<br>0 ( ) (1 ) 2 (1 ) [ (1 ) ]3<br>2 (1 ) 3 (multiplying by (1 ) )<br>22 3 2<br>2 2 1.26.<br>df x cx x cx x cx x xdx<br>cx x cx x<br>cx cx cx cx cx<br>xx<br>\u2212\u2212 \u2212\u2032= = + = + + \u2212+<br>= +\u2212 +<br>= +\u2212= \u2212<br>=\u2212 \u21d2= =<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q143. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "The lifetime of a light bulb has density function, f , where f(x) is proportional to<br><br>2<br>3 ,0 51<br>x xx &lt;&lt;+ , and 0, otherwise.<br><br>Calculate the mode of this distribution.<br><br>A) 0.00<br>B) 0.79<br>C) 1.26<br>D) 4.42<br>E) 5.00", "tags": ["ExamP::UnivariateRV", "ExamP::UnivariateRV::ContinuousDistributions"]},
    {"back": "<b>Answer: C) 0.71</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>It is not necessary to determine the constant of proportionality. Let it be c. To determine the<br>mode, set the derivative of the density function equal to zero and solve.<br>22 22<br>2<br>2<br>2<br>1/2<br>0 ( ) (2 ) (1 2 )<br>1 2 (multiplying by ce )<br>(1/ 2) 0.71.<br>xx xx<br>x<br>df x cxe ce cx x e ce xdx<br>x<br>x<br>\u2212\u2212 \u2212\u2212\u2032= = = \u2212= \u2212<br>= \u2212<br>\u21d2= =<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q144. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "An insurer\u2019s medical reimbursements have density function f , where f(x) is proportional<br>to<br>2xxe\u2212 , for 0 &lt; x &lt; 1, and 0, otherwise.<br><br>Calculate the mode of the medical reimbursements.<br><br>A) 0.00<br>B) 0.50<br>C) 0.71<br>D) 0.84<br>E) 1.00", "tags": ["ExamP::UnivariateRV", "ExamP::UnivariateRV::ContinuousDistributions"]},
    {"back": "<b>Answer: E) 0.78</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>A geometric probability distribution with mean 1.5 will have p = 2/3. So Pr(1 visit) = 2/3, P(two<br>visits) = 2/9, etc. There are four disjoint scenarios in which total admissions will be two or less.<br><br>Scenario 1: No employees have hospital admissions. Probability =<br>50.8 0.32768= .<br><br>Scenario 2: One employee has one admission and the other employees have none. Probability =<br>45 (0.2)(0.8) (2/3) 0.273071<br>\uf8eb\uf8f6 =\uf8ec\uf8f7\uf8ed\uf8f8<br>.<br><br>Scenario 3: One employee has two admissions and the other employees have none. Probability =<br>45 (0.2)(0.8) (2/9) 0.091021<br>\uf8eb\uf8f6 =\uf8ec\uf8f7\uf8ed\uf8f8<br>.<br><br>Scenario 4: Two employees each have one admission and the other three employees have none.<br>Probability =<br>235 (0.2) (0.8) (2/3)(2/3) 0.091022<br>\uf8eb\uf8f6 =\uf8ec\uf8f7\uf8ed\uf8f8<br>.<br><br>The total probability is 0.78279.<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q145. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "A company has five employees on its health insurance plan. Each year, each employee<br>independently has an 80% probability of no hospital admissions. If an employee requires<br>one or more hospital admissions, the number of admissions is modeled by a geometric<br>distribution with a mean of 1.50. The numbers of hospital admissions of different<br>employees are mutually independent.<br><br>Each hospital admission costs 20,000.<br><br>Calculate the probability that the company\u2019s total hospital costs in a year are less than<br>50,000.<br><br>A) 0.41<br>B) 0.46<br>C) 0.58<br>D) 0.69<br>E) 0.78", "tags": ["ExamP::GeneralProbability", "ExamP::GeneralProbability::Independence"]},
    {"back": "<b>Answer: C) 0.148<br>(D 0.230</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>The intersection of the two events (third malfunction on the fifth day and not three malfunctions<br>on first three days) is the same as the first of those events. So the numerator of the conditional<br>probability is the negative binomial probability of the third success (malfunction) on the fifth<br>day, which is<br>224 (0.4) (0.6) (0.4) 0.138242<br>\uf8eb\uf8f6 =\uf8ec\uf8f7\uf8ed\uf8f8<br>.<br>The denominator is the probability of not having three malfunctions in three days, which is<br>31 (0.4) 0.936\u2212= .<br>The conditional probability is 0.13824/0.936 = 0.1477.<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q146. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "On any given day, a certain machine has either no malfunctions or exactly one<br>malfunction. The probability of malfunction on any given day is 0.40. Machine<br>malfunctions on different days are mutually independent.<br><br>Calculate the probability that the machine has its third malfunction on the fifth day, given<br>that the machine has not had three malfunctions in the first three days.<br><br>A) 0.064<br>B) 0.138<br>C) 0.148<br>(D 0.230<br>E) 0.246", "tags": ["ExamP::GeneralProbability", "ExamP::GeneralProbability::Independence"]},
    {"back": "<b>Answer: C) 0.35</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>Let<br>ip represent the probability that the patient&#x27;s cancer is in stage i, for i = 0, 1, 2, 3, or 4.<br>The probabilities must sum to 1. That fact and the three facts given the question produce the<br>following equations.<br><br>01234<br>012<br>1234<br>0134<br>1<br>0.75<br>0.8<br>0.8<br>ppppp<br>ppp<br>pppp<br>pppp<br>++++=<br>++=<br>+++=<br>+++=<br>.<br><br>Therefore, we have<br>( )<br>( )<br>0 01234 1234<br>2 01234 0134<br>1 012 02<br>( ) 1 0.8 0.2<br>( ) 1 0.8 0.2<br>( ) 0.75 0.2 0.2 0.35.<br>p ppppp pppp<br>p ppppp pppp<br>p ppp pp<br>= ++++ \u2212 +++ = \u2212 =<br>= ++++ \u2212 +++ = \u2212 =<br>= ++ \u2212\u2212= \u2212 \u2212 =<br>.<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q147. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "In a certain group of cancer patients, each patient&#x27;s cancer is classified in exactly one of<br>the following five stages: stage 0, stage 1, stage 2, stage 3, or stage 4.<br><br>i) 75% of the patients in the group have stage 2 or lower.<br>ii) 80% of the patients in the group have stage 1 or higher.<br>iii) 80% of the patients in the group have stage 0, 1, 3, or 4.<br><br>One patient from the group is randomly selected.<br><br>Calculate the probability that the selected patient&#x27;s cancer is stage 1.<br><br>A) 0.20<br>B) 0.25<br>C) 0.35<br>D) 0.48<br>E) 0.65", "tags": ["ExamP::GeneralProbability"]},
