    {"back": "<b>Answer: A) 0.55</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>The town experiences one tornado every 0.8 years on average, which is the mean of the<br>exponential distribution. The median is found from<br><br>/0.80.5 [ ] 1<br>ln(0.5) / 0.8<br>0.8ln(0.5) 0.55.<br>mPX m e<br>m<br>m<br>\u2212= \u2264= \u2212<br>=\u2212<br>= \u2212=<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q214. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "A certain town experiences an average of 5 tornadoes in any four year period. The<br>number of years from now until the town experiences its next tornado as well as the<br>number of years between tornados have identical exponential distributions and all such<br>times are mutually independent<br><br>Calculate the median number of years from now until the town experiences its next<br>tornado.<br><br>A) 0.55<br>B) 0.73<br>C) 0.80<br>D) 0.87<br>E) 1.25", "tags": ["ExamP::UnivariateRV", "ExamP::UnivariateRV::ContinuousDistributions"]},
    {"back": "<b>Answer: A) 1.77</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>Let X = the amount of a loss. Ignoring the deductible, the median loss is the solution to<br>0.25 0.25 0.250.5 [ ] 0.25 0 ( ) x mm<br>m<br>P X m e dx e e<br>\u221e<br>\u2212 \u2212\u2212= &gt; = = \u2212\u2212 =\u222b which is m = \u20134(ln0.5) = 2.77.<br>Because 2.77 &gt; 1, the loss exceeds 2.77 if and only if the claim payment exceeds<br>2.77 \u2013 1 = 1.77, which is therefore the median claim payment.<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q215. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "Losses under an insurance policy are exponentially distributed with mean 4. The<br>deductible is 1 for each loss.<br><br>Calculate the median amount that the insurer pays a policyholder for a loss under the<br>policy.<br><br>A) 1.77<br>B) 2.08<br>C) 2.12<br>D) 2.77<br>E) 3.12", "tags": ["ExamP::UnivariateRV", "ExamP::UnivariateRV::ContinuousDistributions"]},
