    {"back": "<b>Answer: E) 44.6</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>X has an exponential distribution with mean 8 and variance 64. The second moment is 128. The<br>mean and second moment of Z are both 0.45. Then (using the independence of X and Z),<br>2 22<br>2<br>( ) ( ) ( ) 0.45(8)<br>[( ) ] ( ) ( ) 0.45(128) 57.6<br>( ) 57.6 3.6 44.64.<br>EZ X EZEX<br>E ZX E Z E X<br>Var ZX<br>= =<br>= = =<br>=\u2212=<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q242. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "Let X denote the loss amount sustained by an insurance company\u2019s policyholder in an<br>auto collision. Let Z denote the portion of X that the insurance company will have to pay.<br>An actuary determines that X and Z are independent with respective density and<br>probability functions<br><br>/8(1 / 8) , 0()<br>0, otherwise<br>xexfx<br>\u2212\uf8f1 &gt;=\uf8f2<br>\uf8f3<br><br>and<br>0.45, 1[] 0.55, 0.<br>zPZ z z<br>=\uf8f1= = \uf8f2 =\uf8f3<br><br><br>Calculate the variance of the insurance company\u2019s claim payment ZX.<br><br>A) 13.0<br>B) 15.8<br>C) 28.8<br>D) 35.2<br>E) 44.6", "tags": ["ExamP::GeneralProbability", "ExamP::GeneralProbability::Independence"]},
    {"back": "<b>Answer: B) 90</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>Each (x,y) pair has probability 1/25. There are only three possible benefit amounts:<br>0: Occurs only for the pair (0.0) and so the probability is 1/25.<br>50: Occurs for the three pairs (0,1), (1,0), and (1,1) and so the probability is 3/25.<br>100: Occurs in all remaining cases and so the probability is 21/25.<br>The expected value is 0(1/25) + 50(3/25) + 100(21/25) = 2250/25 = 90.<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q243. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "A couple takes out a medical insurance policy that reimburses them for days of work<br>missed due to illness. Let X and Y denote the number of days missed during a given<br>month by the wife and husband, respectively. The policy pays a monthly benefit of 50<br>times the maximum of X and Y, subject to a benefit limit of 100. X and Y are<br>independent, each with a discrete uniform distribution on the set {0,1,2,3,4}.<br><br>Calculate the expected monthly benefit for missed days of work that is paid to the couple.<br><br>A) 70<br>B) 90<br>C) 92<br>D) 95<br>E) 140", "tags": ["ExamP::UnivariateRV", "ExamP::UnivariateRV::DiscreteDistributions"]},
    {"back": "<b>Answer: B) 0.099</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>The marginal distribution for the probability of a given number of hospitalizations can be<br>calculated by adding the columns. Then p(0) = 0.915, p(1) = 0.072, p(2) = 0.012, and p(3) =<br>0.001. The expected value is 0.915(0) + 0.072(1) + 0.012(2) + 0.001(3) = 0.099.<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q244. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "The table below shows the joint probability function of a sailor\u2019s number of boating<br>accidents and number of hospitalizations from these accidents this year.<br><br><br>Number of Hospitalizations from Accidents<br>Number of<br>Accidents<br>0 1 2 3<br>0 0.700<br>1 0.150 0.050<br>2 0.060 0.020 0.010<br>3 0.005 0.002 0.002 0.001<br><br>Calculate the sailor\u2019s expected number of hospitalizations from boating accidents this<br>year.<br><br>A) 0.085<br>B) 0.099<br>C) 0.410<br>D) 1.000<br>E) 1.500", "tags": ["ExamP::MultivariateRV", "ExamP::MultivariateRV::JointDistributions"]},
    {"back": "<b>Answer: E) 1744</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>Let S be the speed and X be the loss. Given S, X has an exponential distribution with mean 3X.<br>Then, noting that the variance of an exponential random variable is the square of the mean, the<br>variance of a uniform random variable is the square of the range divided by 12, and for any<br>random variable the second moment is the variance plus the square of the mean:<br>2<br>2 22<br>() [( |) ] [ ( |)<br>[3 ] (9 )<br>9(20 5) /12 9[(20 5) /12 12.5 ]<br>1743.75.<br>Var X Var E X S E Var X S<br>Var S E S<br>= +<br>= +<br>= \u2212+ \u2212+<br>=<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q245. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "On Main Street, a driver\u2019s speed just before an accident is uniformly distributed on<br>[5, 20]. Given the speed, the resulting loss from the accident is exponentially distributed<br>with mean equal to three times the speed.<br><br>Calculate the variance of a loss due to an accident on Main Street.<br><br>A) 525<br>B) 1463<br>C) 1575<br>D) 1632<br>E) 1744", "tags": ["ExamP::UnivariateRV", "ExamP::UnivariateRV::ContinuousDistributions"]},
    {"back": "<b>Answer: C) 2.93</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>The four possible outcomes for which X + Y = 3 are given below, with their probabilities.<br>3 2.3<br>1.7 4<br>1.7 2 2.3<br>4<br>2 1.7 2.3<br>4<br>3 1.7<br>2.3 4<br>2.3(0,3) : 2.02783!<br>1.7 2.3(1, 2) : 4.49651! 2!<br>1.7 2.3(2,1) : 3.32352! 1!<br>1.7(3,0) : 0.8188 .3!<br>eee<br>ee e<br>e e e<br>e e e<br>\u2212<br>\u2212\u2212<br>\u2212\u2212<br>\u2212<br>\u2212\u2212<br>\u2212<br>\u2212<br>\u2212\u2212<br>=<br>=<br>=<br>=<br><br>The conditional probabilities are found by dividing the above probabilities by their sum. They<br>are, 0.1901, 0.4215, 0.3116, 0.0768, respectively. These apply to the X \u2013 Y values of \u20133, \u20131, 1,<br>and 3. The mean is \u20133(0.1901) \u20131(0.4215) + 1(0.3116) + 3(0.0768) = \u20130.4498. The second<br>moment is 9(0.1901) + 1(0.4215) + 1(0.3116) + 9(0.0768) = 3.1352. The variance is 2.9329.<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q246. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "Let X be the annual number of hurricanes hitting Florida, and let Y be the annual number<br>of hurricanes hitting Texas. X and Y are independent Poisson variables with respective<br>means 1.70 and 2.30.<br><br>Calculate<br>Var( | 3)X YX Y\u2212 += .<br><br>A) 1.71<br>B) 1.77<br>C) 2.93<br>D) 3.14<br>E) 4.00", "tags": ["ExamP::UnivariateRV", "ExamP::UnivariateRV::DiscreteDistributions"]},
    {"back": "<b>Answer: A) 2/5</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>The marginal distribution of X has probability 1/5 + a at 0, 2a + b at 1, and 1/5 + b at 2. Due to<br>symmetry, the mean is 1 and so the variance is<br>22(0 1) (1 / 5 ) (1 0) (1 / 5 ) 2 / 5 2a aa\u2212 ++\u2212 + = +<br>which is minimized at a = 0. The marginal distribution of Y is the same as that of X and thus has<br>the same variance, 2/5 + 0 = 2/5.<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q247. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "Random variables X and Y have joint distribution<br><br>X = 0 X = 1 X = 2<br>Y = 0 1/15 a 2/15<br>Y = 1 a b a<br>Y = 2 2/15 a 1/15<br><br>Let a be the value that minimizes the variance of X.<br><br>Calculate the variance of Y.<br><br>A) 2/5<br>B) 8/15<br>C) 16/25<br>D) 2/3<br>E) 7/10", "tags": ["ExamP::MultivariateRV", "ExamP::MultivariateRV::JointDistributions"]},
    {"back": "<b>Answer: C) Cov( X, Y) = 0; the random variables X and Y are dependent.</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>32<br>3<br>2<br>( ,) ( ) ( )() ( ) ( )( )<br>() ( )( 1 / 3 ) ( 1 0 1 )0<br>( ) (1 / 3)(1 0 1) 2 / 3<br>( , ) 0 0(2 / 3) 0.<br>C o vXY EX Y EXE Y EX EXEX<br>EX EX<br>EX<br>Cov X Y<br>= \u2212= \u2212<br>= = \u2212++ =<br>= ++=<br>= \u2212=<br><br>They are dependent, because<br>2Pr( 0, 0) Pr( 0, 0) Pr( 0) 1/3<br>Pr( 0)Pr( 0) (1/3)(1/3) 1/9 1/3.<br>XY X X X<br>XY<br>= = = = = = = =<br>= = = = \u2260<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q248. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "Let X be a random variable that takes on the values \u20131, 0, and 1 with equal probabilities.<br><br>Let<br>2YX= .<br><br>Which of the following is true?<br><br>A) Cov( X, Y) &gt; 0; the random variables X and Y are dependent.<br>B) Cov( X, Y) &gt; 0; the random variables X and Y are independent.<br>C) Cov( X, Y) = 0; the random variables X and Y are dependent.<br>D) Cov( X, Y) = 0; the random variables X and Y are independent.<br>E) Cov( X, Y) &lt; 0; the random variables X and Y are dependent.", "tags": ["ExamP::MultivariateRV"]},
    {"back": "<b>Answer: B) 0.50</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>Let X and Y be the two independent losses and Z = min(X,Y). Then,<br>2<br>2<br>Pr( ) Pr( and ) Pr( ) Pr( )<br>( ) Pr( ) 1 Pr( ) 1 ,<br>zz z<br>z<br>Z<br>Zz Xz Yz Xz Yz e e e<br>Fz Z z Z z e<br>\u2212\u2212 \u2212<br>\u2212<br>&gt;= &gt; &gt;= &gt; &gt;= =<br>= \u2264= \u2212 &gt;= \u2212<br><br>which can be recognized as an exponential distribution with mean 1/2.<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q249. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "Losses follow an exponential distribution with mean 1. Two independent losses are<br>observed.<br><br>Calculate the expected value of the smaller loss.<br><br>A) 0.25<br>B) 0.50<br>C) 0.75<br>D) 1.00<br>E) 1.50", "tags": ["ExamP::UnivariateRV", "ExamP::UnivariateRV::ContinuousDistributions"]},
    {"back": "<b>Answer: B) 0.23</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>Let X and Y be the miles driven by the two cars. The total cost, is then C = 3(X/15 + Y/30) =<br>0.2X + 0.1Y. C has a normal distribution with mean 0.2(25) + 0.1(25) = 7.5 and variance 0.04(9)<br>+ 0.01(9) = 0.45. Then, Pr( 7) Pr( (7 7.5) / 0.45 0.7454) 0.23.CZ&lt;= &lt;\u2212 = \u2212 =<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q250. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "A delivery service owns two cars that consume 15 and 30 miles per gallon. Fuel costs 3<br>per gallon. On any given business day, each car travels a number of miles that is<br>independent of the other and is normally distributed with mean 25 miles and standard<br>deviation 3 miles.<br><br>Calculate the probability that on any given business day, the total fuel cost to the delivery<br>service will be less than 7.<br><br>A) 0.13<br>B) 0.23<br>C) 0.29<br>D) 0.38<br>E) 0.47", "tags": ["ExamP::GeneralProbability", "ExamP::GeneralProbability::Independence"]},
    {"back": "<b>Answer: B) 0.100</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>Let X denote the first estimate and Y the second. Then,<br>Pr( 1.2 ) Pr( 1.2 0).X Y XY&gt; = \u2212&gt; W = X<br>\u2013 1.2Y has a normal distribution with mean 1(10b) \u2013 1.2(10b) = \u20132b and variance<br>22 22 21 1.2 2.44bb b+= . Then,<br>2Pr( 0) Pr( (0 2 )/ 2.44 1.280) 0.100.W Zbb&gt;= &gt;+ = =<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q251. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "Two independent estimates are to be made on a building damaged by fire. Each estimate<br>is normally distributed with mean 10b and variance<br>2b .<br><br>Calculate the probability that the first estimate is at least 20 percent higher than the<br>second.<br><br>A) 0.023<br>B) 0.100<br>C) 0.115<br>D) 0.221<br>E) 0.444", "tags": ["ExamP::UnivariateRV", "ExamP::UnivariateRV::ContinuousDistributions"]},
    {"back": "<b>Answer: C) 5/2</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>Let<br>\u00b5 be the common mean. Then the standard deviations of X and Y are 3\u00b5 and 4\u00b5<br>respectively. The mean and variance of (X + Y)/2 are then ( )/2\u00b5\u00b5 \u00b5+= and<br>22 2[(3 ) (4 ) ]/4 25 /4\u00b5\u00b5 \u00b5+= respectively. The coefficient of variation is<br>225 /4 5/2.\u00b5<br>\u00b5 =<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q252. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "The independent random variables X and Y have the same mean. The coefficients<br>of variation of X and Y are 3 and 4 respectively.<br><br>Calculate the coefficient of variation of<br>1 ()2 XY+ .<br><br>A) 5/4<br>B) 7/4<br>C) 5/2<br>D) 7/2<br>E) 7", "tags": ["ExamP::MultivariateRV"]},
    {"back": "<b>Answer: D) 43</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>Var(Z) = Var(3X + 2Y \u2013 5) = 9Var(X) + 4Var(Y) = 9(3) + 4(4) = 43.<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q253. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "Points scored by a game participant can be modeled by Z = 3X + 2Y \u2013 5. X and Y are<br>independent random variables with Var (X) = 3 and Var (Y) = 4.<br><br>Calculate Var (Z).<br><br>A) 12<br>B) 17<br>C) 38<br>D) 43<br>E) 68", "tags": ["ExamP::GeneralProbability", "ExamP::GeneralProbability::Independence"]},
    {"back": "<b>Answer: E) 23.75</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>The mean is the weighted average of the three means: 0.1(20) + 0.3(15) + 0.6(10) = 12.5. The<br>second moment is the weighted average of the three second moments (each of which is the<br>square of the mean plus the mean, for a Poisson distribution): 0.1(420) + 0.3(240) + 0.6(110) =<br>180. The variance is the second moment minus the square of the mean, which is 23.75.<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q254. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "An actuary is studying hurricane models. A year is classified as a high, medium, or low<br>hurricane year with probabilities 0.1, 0.3, and 0.6, respectively. The numbers of<br>hurricanes in high, medium, and low years follow Poisson distributions with means 20,<br>15, and 10, respectively.<br><br>Calculate the variance of the number of hurricanes in a randomly selected year.<br><br>A) 11.25<br>B) 12.50<br>C) 12.94<br>D) 13.42<br>E) 23.75", "tags": ["ExamP::UnivariateRV", "ExamP::UnivariateRV::DiscreteDistributions"]},
    {"back": "<b>Answer: B) 102.50</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>Let F be the number of fillings and R be the number of root canals. The total claim for a given<br>policyholder, C, in a year is C = 50F + 0.7(500R) = 50F + 350R.<br><br>We have E(F) = 0.6(0) + 0.2(1) + 0.15(2) + 0.05(3) = 0.65 and E(R) = 0.8(0) + 0.2(1) = 0.2.<br>Then, E(C) = 50(0.65) + 350(0.2) = 102.50.<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q255. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "A dental insurance company pays 100% of the cost of fillings and 70% of the cost of root<br>canals. Fillings and root canals cost 50 and 500 each, respectively.<br><br>The tables below show the probability distributions of the annual number of fillings and<br>annual number of root canals for each of the company\u2019s policyholders.<br><br># of Fillings 0 1 2 3 # of Root Canals 0 1<br>Probability 0.60 0.20 0.15 0.05 Probability 0.80 0.20<br><br>Calculate the expected annual payment per policyholder for fillings and root canals.<br><br>A) 90.00<br>B) 102.50<br>C) 132.50<br>D) 250.00<br>E) 400.00", "tags": ["ExamP::GeneralProbability"]},
    {"back": "<b>Answer: B) 0.35</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>Due to the memoryless property of the exponential distribution, the distribution of the<br>reimbursement given that there is a payment is exponential with the same parameter. Thus<br>6000/0.5 (6000) 1Fe \u03bb\u2212= = \u2212 which implies that 8656.17\u03bb = . The solution is<br>( ) ( )<br>9000/8656.17 3000/8656.17(9000) (3000) 1 1 0.35.FF e e \u2212\u2212\u2212 =\u2212 \u2212\u2212 =<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q256. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "A loss under a liability policy is modeled by an exponential distribution. The insurance<br>company will cover the amount of that loss in excess of a deductible of 2000. The<br>probability that the reimbursement is less than 6000, given that the loss exceeds the<br>deductible, is 0.50.<br><br>Calculate the probability that the reimbursement is greater than 3000 but less than 9000,<br>given that the loss exceeds the deductible.<br><br>A) 0.28<br>B) 0.35<br>C) 0.50<br>D) 0.65<br>E) 0.72", "tags": ["ExamP::UnivariateRV", "ExamP::UnivariateRV::ContinuousDistributions"]},
    {"back": "<b>Answer: E) 95</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>Using the formulas for the variance and mean of the uniform distribution:<br>22 2 22 2<br>2<br>2<br>2<br>2<br>2<br>(100 ) 100 100 200 3(100) 600 3( ) () () 12 2 12<br>40,000 400 4 19,600<br>12 3<br>0 40,000 78, 400 400 4<br>0 100 9,600<br>0 ( 60)( 160)<br>60<br>a a aa a aEX V a rX EX<br>aa<br>aa<br>aa<br>aa<br>a<br>\u2212 + \u2212+ + ++\uf8eb\uf8f6= += + = \uf8ec\uf8f7\uf8ed\uf8f8<br>++= =<br>= \u2212 ++<br>= +\u2212<br>= \u2212+<br>=<br><br>Then, Y is uniform on the interval 1.25(60) = 75 to 100. The 80th percentile is 75 + 0.8(25) = 95.<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q257. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "Let X be the percentage score on a college-entrance exam for students who did not<br>participate in an exam-preparation seminar. X is modeled by a uniform distribution on<br>[a, 100].<br><br>Let Y be the percentage score on a college-entrance exam for students who did participate<br>in an exam-preparation seminar. Y is modeled by a uniform distribution on [1.25a, 100].<br><br>It is given that<br>2 19,600() 3EX = .<br><br>Calculate the 80th percentile of Y.<br><br>A) 80<br>B) 85<br>C) 90<br>D) 92<br>E) 95", "tags": ["ExamP::UnivariateRV", "ExamP::UnivariateRV::ContinuousDistributions"]},
    {"back": "<b>Answer: C) 2450</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>Using a Venn Diagram (calling the risk factors A, B, C) we get 400 + 300 + X + Y = 1000 (circle<br>A), 400 + 300 + X + Z = 1000 (circle B), 400 + 300 + Y + Z= 1000 (circle C). Using the first 2<br>equations we get Y = Z, and using the second 2 equations we get X = Y. Thus X = Y = Z = 150,<br>and so the total number of participants is 3(400) + 3(150) + 300 + 500 = 2450.<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q258. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "In a study of driver safety, drivers were categorized according to three risk factors.<br>Exactly 1000 drivers exhibited each individual risk factor. Also, for each of the risk<br>factors, there were exactly 400 drivers exhibiting that risk factor and neither of the other<br>two risk factors. Finally, there were exactly 300 drivers who exhibited all three risk<br>factors and 500 who exhibited none of the three risk factors.<br><br>Calculate the number of drivers in the study.<br><br>A) 2000<br>B) 2300<br>C) 2450<br>D) 2750<br>E) 3500", "tags": ["ExamP::GeneralProbability"]},
