    {"back": "<b>Answer: D) 0.680</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>Let X be the number of appraisals below \u03b8. X is binomial with n = 4, p = 0.75.<br>We need exactly 1, 2 or 3 successes for the event L &lt; \u03b8 &lt; H to occur. The probability is<br>P( 1) P( 2) P( 3)XX X= += += =<br>1 32 23 1444(0.75) (0.25) (0.75) (0.25) (0.75) (0.25)123<br>\uf8eb\uf8f6 \uf8eb\uf8f6 \uf8eb\uf8f6++\uf8ec\uf8f7 \uf8ec\uf8f7 \uf8ec\uf8f7\uf8ed\uf8f8 \uf8ed\uf8f8 \uf8ed\uf8f8<br>= 0.0469 + 0.2109 + 0.4219 =<br>0.6797.<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q285. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "Appraisals of the value of a necklace are uniformly distributed on the interval<br>[ 3, 1]\u03b8\u03b8\u2212+ , where \u03b8 is the actual price the owner paid for the necklace. Four mutually<br>independent appraisals are obtained.<br><br>Let L denote the lowest of the four appraisals and H the highest.<br><br>Calculate P[L &lt; \u03b8 &lt; H].<br><br>A) 0.152<br>B) 0.188<br>C) 0.600<br>D) 0.680<br>E) 0.996<br><br><br><br>286, Losses follow an exponential distribution with mean 1. Two independent losses are<br>observed.<br><br>Calculate the probability that either of the losses is more than twice the other.<br><br>(A)<br>6<br>1<br>(B)<br>4<br>1<br>(C)<br>3<br>1<br>(D)<br>2<br>1<br>(E)<br>3<br>2", "tags": ["ExamP::UnivariateRV", "ExamP::UnivariateRV::ContinuousDistributions"]},
    {"back": "<b>Answer: D) 0.53</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>Let WP denote the event \u201cWoman is Pregnant\u201d, WNP the event \u201cWoman is Not Pregnant\u201d, and<br>TP the event \u201cTest Shows Pregnancy\u201d. Using Bayes Theorem:<br><br>P( | )*P( )P( | ) P( | )*P( ) P( | )*P( )<br>(1 0.1)(0.2) 0.18 0.5294(1 0.1)(0.2) (0.2)(1 0.2) 0.34<br>TP WP WPWP TP TP WP WP TP WNP WNP= +<br>\u2212= = =\u2212 +\u2212<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q288. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "For a pregnant woman, a certain test will give the outcome \u201cnot pregnant\u201d with<br>probability 0.10. For a non-pregnant woman, the test will give the outcome \u201cpregnant\u201d<br>with probability 0.20. Of women who take the test, 20% are pregnant.<br><br>Calculate the probability that a woman is pregnant, given her test outcome is \u201cpregnant.\u201d<br><br>A) 0.10<br>B) 0.20<br>C) 0.50<br>D) 0.53<br>E) 0.90", "tags": ["ExamP::GeneralProbability"]},
    {"back": "<b>Answer: A) 163.5</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>The probability function of Y, the amount paid in thousands, is<br><br>0.72 0<br>0.14 200() 0.06 400<br>0.08 500<br>y<br>ypy y<br>y<br>=\uf8f1<br>\uf8f4 =\uf8f4=\uf8f2 =\uf8f4<br>\uf8f4 =\uf8f3<br><br><br>E(Y) = 200 * 0.14 + 400 * 0.06 + 500 * 0.08 = 28 + 24 + 40 = 92<br>E(Y<br>2) = 2002 * 0.14 + 4002 * 0.06 + 5002 * 0.08 = 35200<br>Var(Y) = E(Y2) \u2013 (E(Y))2 = 35200 \u2013 922 = 26736<br>SD(Y)=26,7360.5 = 163.5115<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q289. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "An airport owner purchases an insurance policy to offset costs associated with excessive<br>amounts of snowfall. For every full ten inches of snow in excess of 40 inches during the<br>winter season, the insurer pays the airport 200 up to a policy maximum of 500.<br><br>The following table shows a probability function for the random variable X of winter<br>season snowfall, in inches, at the airport.<br><br>Inches of Snowfall (x) p(x)<br>0 20x\u2264&lt; 0.06<br>20 30x\u2264&lt; 0.18<br>30 40x\u2264&lt; 0.26<br>40 50x\u2264&lt; 0.22<br>50 60x\u2264&lt; 0.14<br>60 70x\u2264&lt; 0.06<br>70 80x\u2264&lt; 0.04<br>80 90x\u2264&lt; 0.04<br>90 x\u2264 0.00<br><br>Calculate the standard deviation of the amount paid under the policy.<br><br>A) 163.5<br>B) 187.6<br>C) 208.7<br>D) 234.9<br>E) 336.6", "tags": ["ExamP::UnivariateRV", "ExamP::UnivariateRV::ExpectationVariance"]},
