    {"back": "<b>Answer: C) 0.26</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>E(X) = 0.25*1 + 0.375*1 = 0.625<br>E(Y) = 0.125*1 + 0.375 = 0.500<br>E(XY) = P[X = 1, Y = 1] = 0.375<br>Var(X) = 0.625 \u2013 0.625<br>2 = 0.234<br>Var(Y) = 0.5 \u2013 0.52 = 0.25<br>Cov(X,Y)=E(XY)-E(X)E(Y) = 0.375 \u2013 0.625*0.500 = 0.0625<br>Corr(X,Y) = 0.0625/(0.234*0.25)1/2 = 0.258<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q291. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "Let X and Y be discrete random variables with joint probability function<br><br>\uf8f4<br>\uf8f4<br>\uf8f3<br>\uf8f4\uf8f4<br>\uf8f2<br>\uf8f1<br>= =<br>= =<br>= =<br>= =<br>=<br>. 1 , 1 for , 375 . 0<br>1 , 0 for , 125 . 0<br>0 , 1 for , 250 . 0<br>0 , 0 for , 250 . 0<br>) , (<br>y x<br>y x<br>y x<br>y x<br>y x p<br><br>Calculate Corr (X, Y), the correlation coefficient of X and Y.<br><br>A) 0.06<br>B) 0.23<br>C) 0.26<br>D) 0.38<br>E) 0.63", "tags": ["ExamP::MultivariateRV", "ExamP::MultivariateRV::CovarianceCorrelation"]},
    {"back": "<b>Answer: B) 2.22</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>6 / 21 0<br>5 / 21 1<br>4 / 21 2() 3 / 21 3<br>2 / 21 4<br>1/ 21 5<br>y<br>y<br>ypy y<br>y<br>y<br>=\uf8f1<br>\uf8f4 =\uf8f4<br>\uf8f4 ==\uf8f2 =\uf8f4<br>\uf8f4 =\uf8f4 =\uf8f3<br><br><br>E(Y) = 0*6/21 + 1*5/21 + 2*4/21 + 3*3/21 + 4*2/21 + 5*1/21 = 1.67<br>E(Y<br>2) = 0*6/21 + 1*5/21 + 4*4/21 + 9*3/21 + 16*2/21 + 25*1/21 = 5<br>Var(Y) = 5 \u2013 (1.67)2 = 2.22<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q292. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "Let X and Y be discrete random variables with joint probability function<br><br>\uf8f4\uf8f3<br>\uf8f4\uf8f2<br>\uf8f1 ===<br>otherwise., 0<br>, .. ,. 0and5 , .. . , 1 , 0 for ,21<br>1<br>) , ( x yxy x p<br><br>Calculate the variance of Y.<br><br>A) 1.67<br>B) 2.22<br>C) 3.33<br>D) 5.00<br>E) 5.56", "tags": ["ExamP::MultivariateRV", "ExamP::MultivariateRV::JointDistributions"]},
    {"back": "<b>Answer: D) 16.6</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>Let W = X + Y. Then W has the probability function:<br>w p(w)<br>0 0.9729<br>40 0.02<br>80 0.002<br>200 0.004<br>240 0.001<br>400 0.0001<br>For instance, the event {W = 200} is the union of the events {X = 200, Y = 0} and<br>{X = 0, Y = 200}.<br>It follows that E(W) = 2.04, E(W<br>2) = 278.4, and Var (W) = 274.24. Taking the square root gives<br>the standard deviation of 16.56.<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q293. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "A company provides disability benefits to its employees. There are only two possible<br>benefits: partial disability, costing the company 40, and total disability, costing the<br>company 200. The company employs a number of married couples.<br><br>Let (X,Y) denote the company&#x27;s disability costs for a randomly selected employed<br>married couple. The joint probability function for (X,Y) is:<br>x<br>p(x,y) 0 40 200<br>0 0.9729 0.0100 0.0020<br>y 40 0.0100 0.0020 0.0005<br>200 0.0020 0.0005 0.0001<br><br>Calculate the standard deviation of the total disability cost X + Y for the married couple.<br><br>A) 12.3<br>B) 13.8<br>C) 15.7<br>D) 16.6<br>E) 19.8", "tags": ["ExamP::MultivariateRV", "ExamP::MultivariateRV::JointDistributions"]},
    {"back": "<b>Answer: B) The percentage change for Stock X has a larger variance and the means are equal.</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>E [X] = (0.3) (0.18) + (0.50) (0.08) + (0.20) (\u22120.13) = 0.068<br>E [Y] = (0.3) (0.15) + (0.50) (0.08) + 0(.20) (\u22120.06) = 0.068<br><br>V [X] = 0.3 (0.18 \u2212 0.068)2 + .5 (0.08 \u2212 0.068)2 + 0.2 (\u22120.13 \u2212 0.068)2 = .01168<br>V [Y] = 0.3 (0.15 \u2212 0.068)2 + .5 (0.07 \u2212 0.068)2 + 0.2 (\u22120.06 \u2212 0.068)2 = .00529<br><br>So X has a larger variance, but the means are equal.<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q294. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "The probability that the economy will improve, remain stable, or decline is:<br><br>State of the Economy Probability<br>Improve 0.30<br>Remain stable 0.50<br>Decline 0.20<br><br>Prices for Stock X and Stock Y will change as follows:<br><br>State of the Economy Stock X Stock Y<br>Improve Increase 18% Increase 15%<br>Remain stable Increase 8% Increase 7%<br>Decline Decrease 13% Decrease 6%<br><br>Determine which of the following statements about the percentage price changes for<br>Stock X and Stock Y is true.<br><br>A) The percentage change for Stock X has a larger variance and a larger mean.<br>B) The percentage change for Stock X has a larger variance and the means are equal.<br>C) The percentage change for Stock X has a larger variance and a smaller mean.<br>D) The variances are equal and the percentage change for Stock X has a larger mean.<br>E) Both the variances and the means are equal.", "tags": ["ExamP::UnivariateRV", "ExamP::UnivariateRV::ExpectationVariance"]},
    {"back": "<b>Answer: D) 0.84</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>Using the independence of the purchases P(exactly 3 customers purchase)<br>= 3(0.5)<br>2 (0.5)(0.1) + (0.5)3 (0.9) = 0.15, and P(4 purchases = (0.5)3 (0.1) = 0.0125.<br>So P(at most 2) = 1 \u2212 P(3) \u2212 P(4) = 0.1625 = 0.8375.<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q295. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "A company is marketing an investment opportunity to four potential customers. The<br>company believes that its probability of making a sale is 0.5 for each of the first three<br>customers but that it is only 0.1 for the fourth customer. The customers&#x27; purchases are<br>independent of one another.<br><br>Calculate the probability that at most two customers purchase the investment.<br><br>A) 0.38<br>B) 0.46<br>C) 0.54<br>D) 0.84<br>E) 0.90", "tags": ["ExamP::GeneralProbability", "ExamP::GeneralProbability::Independence"]},
    {"back": "<b>Answer: A) 50</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>Let x be the number of policies on male nonsmokers, and let y be the number of policies on<br>female smokers (to be determined). Then, by condition (ii), the number of policies on female<br>nonsmokers is 100 + x, so that the total number of policies on females is 100 + x + y. Next, by<br>condition (iii), the number of policies on male smokers is 350 \u2212 y, so that the number of policies<br>on males is 350 \u2212 y + x. Now, by condition (i), we have<br><br>350 \u2212 y + x = 150 + (100 + x + y).<br><br>After simplification, we obtain: 100 = 2y, which produces y = 50, the number of female smokers.<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q296. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "An actuary compiles the following information about a portfolio of life insurance<br>policies:<br>i) There are 150 more policies on males than there are on females.<br>ii) There are 100 more policies on female nonsmokers than there are on male<br>nonsmokers.<br>iii) There are 350 policies on smokers.<br><br>Calculate the number of policies on female smokers within this portfolio.<br><br>A) 50<br>B) 100<br>C) 200<br>D) 250<br>E) 300", "tags": ["ExamP::GeneralProbability"]},
    {"back": "<b>Answer: C) 0.42</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>Let the random variable X be the future lifetime of a machine part. We know that the density of<br>X has the form f (x) = C(10 + x)<br>\u22122 for 0 &lt; x &lt; 40 (and it is equal to zero otherwise). First,<br>determine the proportionality constant C from the condition 40<br>0 ( ) 1:f x dx\u222b=<br>40 1 40<br>00<br>21 ( ) (10 ) | 25f x dx C x C \u2212= = \u2212+ =\u222b<br>so that C = 25/2 = 12.5. Then,<br>5 2 15<br>00<br>( 5) 12.5(10 ) 12.5(10 ) | 0.8333 1.25 0.4167.P X x dx x\u2212\u2212&lt;= + = \u2212 + = \u2212 + =\u222b<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q297. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "The lifetime of a machine part has a continuous distribution on the interval (0, 40) with<br>probability density function f, where f (x) is proportional to (10 + x)<br>\u22122.<br><br>Calculate the probability that the lifetime of the machine part is less than five.<br><br>A) 0.03<br>B) 0.13<br>C) 0.42<br>D) 0.58<br>E) 0.97", "tags": ["ExamP::UnivariateRV", "ExamP::UnivariateRV::ContinuousDistributions"]},
    {"back": "<b>Answer: A) 0.02</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>E(X) = 0(0.5) + 1(0.2) + 2(0.3) = 0.8<br>E(X<br>2) = 02(0.5) + 12(0.2) + 22(0.3) = 1.4,<br>Var(X) = E(X2) - (E(X))2 = 1.4 \u2212 (0.8)2 = 0.76<br><br>The premium on a policy is 125% of 0.8, which is 1. The total premium on 76 policies is thus<br>76. Let Y be the total claim on 76 policies. By the Central Limit Theorem Y has approximately a<br>normal distribution with mean (76)(0.8) = 60.8 and variance 76(0.76) = 57.76. Consequently,<br>P(Y &gt; 76) \u2248 P(Z &gt;<br>76 60.8[ 76] 2 ,<br>57.76<br>PY P Z \u2212\uf8eb\uf8f6&gt;= &gt; =\uf8ec\uf8f7\uf8ed\uf8f8<br>where Z is the standard normal random<br>variable. The answer is 1 \u2212 \u03a6 (2) = 0.0228.<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q298. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "The claim, X, for a dental insurance policy is a random variable with the following<br>probability function:<br>x P[X = x]<br>0 0.5<br>1 0.2<br>2 0.3<br><br>The premium for the policy is equal to 125% of the expected claim amount.<br><br>Calculate the approximate probability that the total claims on 76 independent policies<br>exceed the total premium collected.<br><br>A) 0.02<br>B) 0.07<br>C) 0.17<br>D) 0.25<br>E) 0.40", "tags": ["ExamP::GeneralProbability", "ExamP::GeneralProbability::Independence"]},
    {"back": "<b>Answer: C) 36</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>For Group A:<br>0<br>[ 0] 0.70 0.35670!<br>A<br>A<br>ePX<br>\u03bb \u03bb \u03bb<br>\u2212<br>= = = \u21d2=<br>For Group B:<br>0<br>[ 0] 0.90 0.10540!<br>B<br>B<br>ePX<br>\u03bb \u03bb \u03bb<br>\u2212<br>= = = \u21d2=<br>For Group C:<br>0<br>[ 0] 0.50 0.69310!<br>C<br>C<br>ePX<br>\u03bb \u03bb \u03bb<br>\u2212<br>= = = \u21d2=<br>Then, 20,000 0.3567 45,000 0.1054 35,000 0.6931 36,136\u00d7+\u00d7+\u00d7=<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q299. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "An insurance company categorizes its policyholders into three mutually exclusive groups.<br>A study produced the following information:<br><br><br><br>Group<br><br>Number of<br>policyholders<br>Probability a<br>policyholder<br>has no claims<br>A<br>B<br>C<br>20,000<br>45,000<br>35,000<br>70%<br>90%<br>50%<br><br>Within each group, the numbers of claims made by individual policyholders are mutually<br>independent Poisson random variables.<br><br>Calculate the expected total number of claims, in thousands, made by the 100,000<br>policyholders.<br><br>A) 21<br>B) 28<br>C) 36<br>D) 64<br>E) 72", "tags": ["ExamP::GeneralProbability", "ExamP::GeneralProbability::SampleSpacesEvents"]},
    {"back": "<b>Answer: E) 0.79</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>( )<br>( )<br>0.288 0<br>0.288 1<br>0.288P 0 claims 0.7500!<br>0.288P 1 claim 0.2161!<br>e<br>e<br>\u2212<br>\u2212<br>= =<br>= =<br><br>For three years the probability of 0 or 1 claim is<br>( ) ( ) ( )( ) ( )<br>32 3<br>1P 0 in 3 years)+P(1 in 3 years 0.75 0.75 0.216 0.79.= +=<br>Alternatively, the number of claims in three years has a Poisson distribution with mean 3(0.288)<br>= 0. 864. The probability of 0 or 1 claims is<br>0.864 0 0.864 10.864 0.864 0.79.0! 1!<br>ee\u2212\u2212<br>+=<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q300. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "A group of insurance policies have all been in force for at least three years. The<br>insurance company plans to pay a dividend on each policy in the group that had no more<br>than one claim incurred on it in the past three years. The number of claims incurred on a<br>policy in any year follows a Poisson distribution with mean 0.288 and the number<br>incurred in any year is independent of the number incurred in any other year.<br><br>Calculate the probability that a policy chosen at random from the group will receive a<br>dividend.<br><br>A) 0.01<br>B) 0.36<br>C) 0.42<br>D) 0.54<br>E) 0.79", "tags": ["ExamP::GeneralProbability", "ExamP::GeneralProbability::Independence"]},
    {"back": "<b>Answer: E) 19</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>Var(Total) = Var(Fire) + Var(Theft) + 2Cov(Fire, Theft) = 5 + 8 + 2(3) = 19.<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q301. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "An insurance company sells a one-year insurance policy that covers fire and theft losses.<br>The variance of the number of fire losses is 5. The variance of the number of theft<br>losses is 8. The covariance between the number of fire and theft losses is 3.<br><br>Calculate the variance of the total number of fire and theft losses covered by this policy.<br><br>A) 7<br>B) 10<br>C) 13<br>D) 16<br>E) 19", "tags": ["ExamP::MultivariateRV", "ExamP::MultivariateRV::CovarianceCorrelation"]},
    {"back": "<b>Answer: A) 1213e\u2212</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>Let 123,,XXX denote the number of accidents in days 1, 2, and 3, respectively.<br>Then, each has Poisson distribution with mean 4. Since the iX s are assumed to be independent,<br>123XX X X=++ has a Poisson distribution with mean 3(4) = 12. Then,<br>[ ] [ ] [ ]<br>12 0 12 1<br>1212 12P2 P0 P1 1 3 .0! 1!<br>eeX XX e<br>\u2212\u2212<br>\u2212&lt;= =+ == + =<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q302. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "The number of automobile accidents on any day in a city has a Poisson distribution with<br>mean 4. The number of accidents on a given day is independent of the number of<br>accidents on any other day.<br><br>Calculate the probability that at most one accident occurs in a three-day period.<br><br>A) 1213e\u2212<br>B) 1272e\u2212<br>C) 1285e\u2212<br>D) 45e\u2212<br>E) 413e\u2212", "tags": ["ExamP::GeneralProbability", "ExamP::GeneralProbability::Independence"]},
    {"back": "<b>Answer: C) 0.141</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>The probability of success is 11 1( )( ) . 88 4p P HHH P TTT= + =+=<br>For the first success to be on the third experiment we need two failures followed by one success.<br>The probability is (3/4)(3/4)(1/4) = 9/64 = 0.141.<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q303. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "An experiment consists of tossing three fair coins and is deemed a success if the result is<br>three heads or three tails. The experiment is repeated until a success occurs.<br><br>Calculate the probability that it takes exactly three experiments to obtain a success.<br><br>A) 0.047<br>B) 0.070<br>C) 0.141<br>D) 0.188<br>E) 0.422", "tags": ["ExamP::GeneralProbability"]},
