    {"back": "<b>Answer: B) 0.417</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>The first die can be any number, so 6 possibilities. If the second die matches (1 possibility) then<br>the third die must not match (5 possibilities). Hence this outcome can occur 6(1)(5) = 30 ways. A<br>second outcome is the second die does not match (5 possibilities), in which case the third die<br>must match one of the first two (2 possibilities), for an additional 60 ways. The desired<br>probability is then 90/216 = 0.417.<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q332. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "Three fair dice are thrown.<br><br>Calculate the probability that the same number appears on exactly two of the three dice.<br><br>A) 0.278<br>B) 0.417<br>C) 0.444<br>D) 0.556<br>E) 0.583", "tags": ["ExamP::GeneralProbability"]},
    {"back": "<b>Answer: D) 0.339</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>Hypergeometric:<br><br>10 7<br>33 75 0.3393717 221<br>6<br>\uf8eb \uf8f6\uf8eb \uf8f6<br>\uf8ec \uf8f7\uf8ec \uf8f7\uf8ed \uf8f8\uf8ed \uf8f8 = =\uf8eb\uf8f6<br>\uf8ec\uf8f7\uf8ed\uf8f8<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q333. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "A group of 17 people in a study on lung cancer consists of three heavy smokers, four<br>light smokers, and ten non-smokers. Six people from the group are chosen at random for<br>a new treatment.<br><br>Calculate the probability that three of those chosen are non-smokers.<br><br>A) 0.176<br>B) 0.284<br>C) 0.300<br>D) 0.339<br>E) 0.588", "tags": ["ExamP::GeneralProbability"]},
    {"back": "<b>Answer: A) 7.50%</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>P(M) = 0.6<br>P(F) = 0.4<br>P(S|M) = 0.20<br>P(F|S) = 0.20<br><br>(| )()( |) (| )() (| )( )<br>( | )(0.4) 0.2(0.2)(0.6)0.2 ( | ) 0.75( | )(0.4) 0.2(0.6) 0.4 0.2(0.4)<br>PS FPFPF S PS FPF PS M PM<br>PS F PS FPS F<br>= +<br>= \u21d2= =+\u2212<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q334. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "A group of health insurance policyholders is composed of 60% men and 40% women. Of<br>the male policyholders, 20% are smokers. Given that a policyholder from the group<br>smokes, the probability that the policyholder is female is 20%.<br><br>Calculate the percentage of female policyholders who are smokers.<br><br>A) 7.50%<br>B) 8.00%<br>C) 12.00%<br>D) 13.33%<br>E) 20.00%", "tags": ["ExamP::GeneralProbability", "ExamP::GeneralProbability::ConditionalProbability"]},
    {"back": "<b>Answer: E) 0.93</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>Hypergeometric:<br><br>82 82<br>21 30 56 56 0.933310 120<br>3<br>\uf8eb\uf8f6 \uf8eb\uf8f6\uf8eb\uf8f6 \uf8eb\uf8f6+\uf8ec\uf8f7 \uf8ec\uf8f7\uf8ec\uf8f7 \uf8ec\uf8f7 +\uf8ed\uf8f8 \uf8ed\uf8f8\uf8ed\uf8f8 \uf8ed\uf8f8 = =\uf8eb\uf8f6<br>\uf8ec\uf8f7\uf8ed\uf8f8<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q335. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "An inspector examines a random sample of three glasses from each incoming box of ten<br>glasses. The inspector accepts the box of ten glasses if at least two of the three examined<br>are found to be in good condition.<br><br>Calculate the probability that a box of ten glasses will be accepted by the inspector if the<br>box contains exactly two glasses that are not in good condition.<br><br>A) 0.10<br>B) 0.47<br>C) 0.70<br>D) 0.90<br>E) 0.93", "tags": ["ExamP::GeneralProbability"]},
    {"back": "<b>Answer: C) 20</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>Let d be the deductible. Assume d &lt; 100 because the expected claim needs to be positive.<br><br>The claim is 0 with probability d/100 (i.e. when the loss does not exceed d), and uniformly<br>distributed over [0, 100 - d] with probability (100 - d)/100 (i.e. when the loss exceeds d).<br><br>Note that the probability that a uniformly distributed random variable is in an interval is<br>proportional to the length of the interval; the expected value is halfway between the minimum<br>and maximum possible values of the uniformly distributed random variable.<br><br>0 (100 ) 10032 [ ] [ * ] [ 0* ]2 100 100<br>d ddE Claim +\u2212 \u2212= = +<br><br>Solving for d gives d = 20 or d = 180; disregard d = 180 &gt; 100.<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q336. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "Losses under an insurance policy are uniformly distributed on the interval [0, 100]. A<br>deductible is set so that the expected claim payment of losses net of the deductible is 32.<br><br>Calculate the deductible.<br><br>A) 9<br>B) 18<br>C) 20<br>D) 36<br>E) 52", "tags": ["ExamP::UnivariateRV", "ExamP::UnivariateRV::ContinuousDistributions"]},
    {"back": "<b>Answer: D) 7.41</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>Let Y represent the loss and X represent the claim. Note that X = 0 if Y \u2264 3; otherwise,<br>X = Y - 3.<br><br>10<br>3<br>3<br>10<br>[ ] ( 3) [ | 3) ( 3) [ | 3)<br>( 3)(0) ( 3) [ 3 | 3]<br>0 * [ ] since exponentials are memoryless.10<br>=10e .<br>y<br>EX PY EX Y PY EX Y<br>PY PY EY Y<br>e dy E Y<br>\u2212\u221e<br>\u2212<br>= \u2264 \u2264+ &gt; &gt;<br>=\u2264 +&gt; \u2212&gt;<br>= + \u222b<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q337. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "An insurance policy has a deductible of 3. Losses under the policy are exponentially<br>distributed with mean 10.<br><br>Calculate the expected claim payment of losses net of the deductible.<br><br>A) 2.59<br>B) 5.19<br>C) 7.00<br>D) 7.41<br>E) 9.63", "tags": ["ExamP::UnivariateRV", "ExamP::UnivariateRV::ContinuousDistributions"]},
    {"back": "<b>Answer: B) 0.15</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>R = # of root canals, F = # of fillings, p(r, f) = P(R = r, F = f)<br>P(R = r | F is at most 1)<br>= P(R = r | F = 0 or 1)<br>= P(R = r AND F = 0 or 1) / P(F = 0 or 1)<br>= [p(r, 0) + p(r, 1)] /[p(0, 0) + p(0, 1) + p(1, 0) + p(1, 1) + p(2, 0) + p(2, 1)]<br><br>P(R = 0 | F = 0 or 1) = (0.40 + 0.26) / (0.40 + 0.26 + 0.04 + 0.03 + 0.01 + 0.01) = 22/25<br>P(R = 1 | F = 0 or 1) = (0.04 + 0.03) / (0.40 + 0.26 + 0.04 + 0.03 + 0.01 + 0.01) = 7/75<br>P(R = 2 | F = 0 or 1) = (0.01 + 0.01) / (0.40 + 0.26 + 0.04 + 0.03 + 0.01 + 0.01) = 2/75<br><br>7 2 11[ | 1] 1 2 0.1466775 75 75ER F \uf8eb\uf8f6\uf8eb\uf8f6\u2264= + = =\uf8ec\uf8f7\uf8ec\uf8f7\uf8ed\uf8f8\uf8ed\uf8f8<br>.<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q338. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "The table below shows the joint probability for the number of root canals and the number<br>of fillings a dental patient undergoes this year.<br><br>Number of Fillings<br><br><br><br>Number of Root<br>Canals<br><br><br>0<br><br>1<br><br>2<br><br>3<br><br>4<br><br>0 0.40 0.26 0.05 0.04 0.01<br><br>1 0.04 0.03 0.03 0.03 0.02<br><br>2 0.01 0.01 0.02 0.03 0.02<br><br>Calculate the expected number of root canals the patient undergoes, given that the patient<br>undergoes at most one filling this year.<br><br>A) 0.11<br>B) 0.15<br>C) 0.17<br>D) 0.33<br>E) 0.91", "tags": ["ExamP::MultivariateRV", "ExamP::MultivariateRV::JointDistributions"]},
    {"back": "<b>Answer: A) 7.27</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>N is Binomial, n=500, p=0.12, q=0.88<br><br>Standard deviation =<br>500(0.12)(0.88) 7.26636=<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q339. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "Let N denote the number of items returned out of the next 500 items sold at a department<br>store. For each item sold, the probability that the item is returned is 0.12. Returns are<br>mutually independent.<br><br>Calculate the standard deviation of N.<br><br>A) 7.27<br>B) 7.75<br>C) 12.75<br>D) 20.98<br>E) 52.80", "tags": ["ExamP::GeneralProbability", "ExamP::GeneralProbability::Independence"]},
