    {"back": "<b>Answer: E) 0.029</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>1180 306<br>15180 566<br>39.5 30( 40) ( ) ( 1.90) 0.0287.5PX PZ PZ<br>\u00b5<br>\u03c3<br>\uf8eb\uf8f6= = \uf8ec\uf8f7\uf8ed\uf8f8<br>\uf8eb\uf8f6 \uf8eb\uf8f6= =\uf8ec\uf8f7 \uf8ec\uf8f7<br>\uf8ed\uf8f8 \uf8ed\uf8f8<br>\u2212\u2265\u2192 &gt; = &gt; =<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q362. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "At a certain airport, 1/6 of all scheduled flights are delayed. Assume that flight delays are<br>mutually independent events.<br><br>Use the normal approximation (with continuity correction) to calculate the probability<br>that at least 40 of the next 180 flights are delayed.<br><br>A) 0.011<br>B) 0.014<br>C) 0.018<br>D) 0.023<br>E) 0.029", "tags": ["ExamP::GeneralProbability", "ExamP::GeneralProbability::Independence"]},
    {"back": "<b>Answer: E) 0.727</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>Let H be the event that the policyholder undergoes hospitalization this year.<br>Let A be the event that the policyholder is in class A.<br>P(A) = 12,000/30,000 = 0.4; P(B) = 18,000/30,000 = 0.6<br>P(H|A) = 1 - 0.98 = 0.02; P(H|B) = 1 - 0.995 = 0.005.<br>P(A|H) = P(A)P(H|A) / [P(A)P(H|A) + P(B)P(H|B)] by Bayes&#x27; Theorem<br>= ( 0.4)(0.02) / [(0.4)(0.02) + (0.6)(0.005)]<br>= 0.008 / 0.011 = 0.7272<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q363. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "In a group of 30,000 health insurance policyholders, 12,000 are in Class A and 18,000 are<br>in Class B.<br><br>This year, each policyholder in Class A has probability 0.98 of not undergoing<br>hospitalization; each policyholder in Class B has probability 0.995 of not undergoing<br>hospitalization.<br><br>A randomly chosen policyholder in the group undergoes hospitalization this year.<br><br>Calculate the probability that this policyholder is in Class A.<br><br>A) 0.011<br>B) 0.020<br>C) 0.396<br>D) 0.400<br>E) 0.727", "tags": ["ExamP::GeneralProbability"]},
    {"back": "<b>Answer: D) 0.693</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>Let X be the random variable that a part works. Then:<br>0.2<br>0.2<br>()<br>( )1<br>x<br>x<br>PX x e<br>PX x e<br>\u2212<br>\u2212<br>&gt;=<br>&lt;= \u2212<br><br>One year from now,<br>P[both parts will work | at least 1 part will work]<br>[ ]<br>[ ]<br>both parts will work<br>at least 1 part will work<br>P<br>P=<br>0.2 0.2<br>0.2 0.2<br>0.2 0.2<br>1 (neither part works)<br>1 (1 )(1 )<br>0.67032 0.693100.96714<br>ee<br>P<br>ee<br>ee<br>\u2212\u2212<br>\u2212\u2212<br>\u2212\u2212<br>\u2212<br>= \u2212\u2212 \u2212<br>= =<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q364. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "A two-part machine functions when at least one of its parts is working. Both parts are<br>working today. The future lifetime of each part is exponentially distributed with mean<br>five years. The lifetimes of the parts are independent.<br><br>The machine functions one year from now.<br><br>Calculate the probability that both parts will be working at that time.<br><br>A) 0.003<br>B) 0.409<br>C) 0.670<br>D) 0.693<br>E) 0.819", "tags": ["ExamP::GeneralProbability", "ExamP::GeneralProbability::Independence"]},
    {"back": "<b>Answer: E) 0.93</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>P[no root canal | no fillings] = P[no root canals and no fillings] / P[no fillings]<br>= {1 \u2013 P[at least 1 root canal or filling]} / P[no fillings]<br>= (1 \u2013 0.35)/0.7 = 13/14 = 0.92857.<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q365. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "This year, a dental insurance policyholder has probability 0.70 of having no fillings,<br>probability 0.90 of having no root canals, and probability 0.35 of having at least one<br>filling or root canal.<br><br>Calculate the probability that a policyholder has no root canals, given that the<br>policyholder has no fillings.<br><br>A) 0.50<br>B) 0.65<br>C) 0.72<br>D) 0.78<br>E) 0.93", "tags": ["ExamP::GeneralProbability", "ExamP::GeneralProbability::ConditionalProbability"]},
    {"back": "<b>Answer: D) 0.417</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>This is a hypergeometric probability:<br>7 33 2<br>10 5<br>35(3) 0.41667252<br>CC<br>C = =<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q366. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "A mover transports ten identical boxes with fragile contents. The contents of seven of<br>these boxes all stay intact after the move.<br><br>The mover randomly chooses five different boxes from the ten to inspect.<br><br>Calculate the probability that the contents of exactly three of these five boxes are all<br>intact.<br><br>A) 0.042<br>B) 0.083<br>C) 0.139<br>D) 0.417<br>E) 0.700", "tags": ["ExamP::GeneralProbability"]},
