    {"back": "<b>Answer: D) 14.4</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>Let \u03b2 be the mean of X. We know that<br>\uf05b \uf05d<br>2/0.2 Pr 2 1<br>8.96284<br>Xe \uf062<br>\uf062<br>\uf02d\uf03d \uf0a3 \uf03d\uf02d<br>\uf03d<br><br>Let t be the time at which 80% of its computers have failed. Then,<br>\uf05b \uf05d<br>/8.96284<br>/8.9628<br>0.8 Pr 1<br>0.2<br>14.42513<br>t<br>t<br>Xt e<br>e<br>t<br>\uf02d<br>\uf02d<br>\uf03d \uf0a3 \uf03d\uf02d<br>\uf03d<br>\uf03d<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q385. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "A computer manufacturer collects data on how long it takes before its computers fail.<br>The time to fail, in years, follows an exponential distribution. Twenty percent of its<br>computers fail within two years.<br><br>The probability a randomly selected computer fails before time t, in years, is 0.80.<br><br>Calculate t.<br><br>A) 3.6<br>B) 7.2<br>C) 8.0<br>D) 14.4<br>E) 16.0", "tags": ["ExamP::UnivariateRV", "ExamP::UnivariateRV::ContinuousDistributions"]},
    {"back": "<b>Answer: D) 12</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>Let N = number of tickets the driver receives, which has a Poisson distribution with mean 4.<br>Note that the total fine is the sum of the integers from 1 to N, which equals<br>( 1)<br>2<br>+NN .<br>So the expected total fine is<br>22( 1)E 0.5 ( ) 0.5 ( ) 0.5 [ ( ) ( ) ( )]2<br>0.5(4 16 4) 12.<br>NN EN EN V a rN EN EN+\uf8ee\uf8f9 = + = ++\uf8ef\uf8fa\uf8f0\uf8fb<br>= ++=<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q386. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "To discourage traffic violations, county C charges each driver a fine of 1 for the driver\u2019s<br>first ticket of this year, 2 for the driver\u2019s second ticket of this year, and generally n for the<br>driver\u2019s nth ticket of this year.<br><br>The number of traffic tickets a certain driver in county C receives this year is Poisson<br>distributed with mean 4.<br><br>Calculate the expected value of the total fine this driver is charged for tickets this year.<br><br>A) 6<br>B) 8<br>C) 10<br>D) 12<br>E) 14", "tags": ["ExamP::UnivariateRV", "ExamP::UnivariateRV::DiscreteDistributions"]},
    {"back": "<b>Answer: C) 0.686</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>The probability that the 2 most recent files are both intact is<br>22<br>0240 ( 2)( 3)<br>51 (<br>1)<br>2<br>d<br>dd<br>d dd<br>\u2212\uf8eb \uf8f6\uf8eb \uf8f6<br>\uf8ec \uf8f7<br>\uf8ec \uf8f7 \u2212\u2212\uf8ed \uf8f8\uf8ed \uf8f8= = \u2212\uf8eb\uf8f6<br>\uf8ec\uf8f7\uf8ed\uf8f8<br>.<br>This leads to<br>22 240 40 51 255 306 0 11 215 306 (11 17)( 18)d d dd dd d d\u2212 =\u2212+ \u21d2 =\u2212+ = \u2212\u2212 .<br>Since d is an integer that is at least 3, the unique solution is d = 18.<br>The probability that the 3 most recent files are all intact is<br>33<br>02 ( 3)( 4) 15(14) 35 0.686.( 1) 18(17) 51<br>2<br>d<br>dd<br>d dd<br>\u2212\uf8eb \uf8f6\uf8eb \uf8f6<br>\uf8ec \uf8f7\uf8ec \uf8f7 \u2212\u2212\uf8ed \uf8f8\uf8ed \uf8f8 = = = =\u2212\uf8eb\uf8f6<br>\uf8ec\uf8f7\uf8ed\uf8f8<br>.<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q387. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "When a computer crashes, each of the data files 1, 2,\u2026, d has the same probability of<br>being corrupted, independently of the other files. Given that a crash causes exactly two<br>of the d files to be corrupted, the probability that neither of the two most recently created<br>files are corrupted is<br>51<br>40 .<br><br>Calculate the probability that none of the three most recently created files are corrupted,<br>given that a crash causes exactly two of the files to be corrupted.<br><br>A) 0.523<br>B) 0.676<br>C) 0.686<br>D) 0.695<br>E) 0.710", "tags": ["ExamP::GeneralProbability", "ExamP::GeneralProbability::ConditionalProbability"]},
    {"back": "<b>Answer: D) 28</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>Let N = number of claims; let X = the benefit paid.<br>P(N = 0) = 0.75; P(N = 1) = 0.25<br>E(X | N = 0) = 0; E(X | N = 1) = 8<br>Var(X | N = 0) = 0; Var(X | N = 1) = 8<br>2 = 64<br>Var(E(X | N)) = 82(0.25)(0.75) = 12 because i) a Bernoulli (0-1) random variable has variance<br>p(1 - p) if p = P(Bernoulli variable = 1), and ii)the variance of 8 times the Bernoulli is 82 times<br>the variance of the Bernoulli<br>E(Var(X | N)) = 0(0.75) + 64(0.25) = 16<br>Var(X) = Var(E(X | N)) + E(Var(X | N)) = 12 + 16 = 28.<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q388. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "Under an insurance policy, no benefit is paid on 75% of the claims filed. The benefits<br>paid on the remaining claims are exponentially distributed with mean 8.<br><br>Calculate the variance of the benefit for a randomly selected claim under this policy.<br><br>A) 2<br>B) 14<br>C) 16<br>D) 28<br>E) 32", "tags": ["ExamP::UnivariateRV", "ExamP::UnivariateRV::ContinuousDistributions"]},
    {"back": "<b>Answer: D) 0.375</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>Let the hats (and men) be A, B, C, and D. There are 24 orderings of the hats drawn. Consider the<br>complement, where at least one man draws his hat.<br>If A is drawn first, all 6 subsequent combinations meet this event.<br>If B is drawn first, combinations ACD,CAD, and DCA meet this event.<br>If C or D is drawn first, each also have three combinations that meet this event.<br>Hence there are 6 + 3 + 3 + 3 = 15 ways to meet the complementary event.<br>The desired probability is (24-15)/24 = 0.375.<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q389. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "Four men at a wedding party throw their hats into a big box. Later, each of them<br>randomly selects a hat from the box and places it on his head.<br><br>Calculate the probability that none of the four men has his own hat on his head.<br><br>A) 0.042<br>B) 0.250<br>C) 0.333<br>D) 0.375<br>E) 0.500", "tags": ["ExamP::GeneralProbability"]},
