    {"back": "<b>Answer: B) 4.73</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>This is a negative binomial distribution. The probability of finding fraud is 0.9(0.2) = 0.18. Let<br>p(x) be the probability of examining x policies. Then,<br>2<br>2<br>22<br>(1) 0<br>(2) 0.18 0.0324<br>(3) 2(0.82)(0.18) 0.0531<br>(4) 3(0.82) (0.18) 0.0654<br>(5) 1 0.0324 0.0531 0.0654 0.8491<br>( ) 2(0.0324) 3(0.0531) 4(0.0654) 5(0.8491) 4.7312.<br>p<br>p<br>p<br>p<br>p<br>EX<br>=<br>= =<br>= =<br>= =<br>= \u2212\u2212\u2212=<br>=+++=<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q413. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "An auditor is examining insurance policies for fraud. A policyholder can only file one<br>claim. The probability of any given policy having a claim is 0.90, and the probability of<br>a claim being fraudulent is 0.20. The auditor picks five policies at random and examines<br>them in order until he finds two fraudulent claims. He then stops examining policies. If<br>he doesn\u2019t find two fraudulent claims, he stops after examining the fifth policy.<br><br>Calculate the expected number of policies he will examine.<br><br>A) 4.68<br>B) 4.73<br>C) 4.78<br>D) 4.83<br>E) 4.88", "tags": ["ExamP::GeneralProbability"]},
    {"back": "<b>Answer: E) 0.60</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>This is a hypergeometric problem.<br>63 63<br>31 40[ 3] [ 4 ]99<br>44<br>0.4762 0.1190 0.5952.<br>PX PX<br>\uf8eb \uf8f6\uf8eb \uf8f6 \uf8eb \uf8f6 \uf8eb \uf8f6<br>\uf8ec \uf8f7\uf8ec \uf8f7 \uf8ec \uf8f7 \uf8ec \uf8f7\uf8ed \uf8f8\uf8ed \uf8f8 \uf8ed \uf8f8 \uf8ed \uf8f8= = += =\uf8eb\uf8f6 \uf8eb\uf8f6<br>\uf8ec\uf8f7 \uf8ec\uf8f7\uf8ed\uf8f8 \uf8ed\uf8f8<br>=+=<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q414. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "An agent markets a new life insurance policy to nine people. Six of the nine have already<br>purchased an insurance product from the agent.<br><br>The agent randomly selects four of the nine people for appointments today.<br><br>Calculate the probability that at least three of the four people with appointments have<br>already purchased an insurance product from the agent.<br><br>A) 0.10<br>B) 0.12<br>C) 0.14<br>D) 0.48<br>E) 0.60", "tags": ["ExamP::GeneralProbability"]},
    {"back": "<b>Answer: B) 17,800</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>Let C be the expected number buying the carriage only<br>S be the expected number buying the seat only<br>B be the expected number buying both<br><br>Then C + S + B + 0.60(200) = 200<br>C + B = 0.20(200) = 40<br>S + B = 0.35(200) = 70<br>40 + 70 \u2013 B + 120 = 200<br>B = 30, C = 10, S = 40<br>Revenue = 10(300) + 40(100) + 30(360) = 17,800<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q415. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "A specialty store sells only baby carriages and car seats. The price of a baby carriage is<br>300 and the price of a car seat is 100. The proprietor knows that 60% of the people<br>stopping at the store do not make a purchase, 20% buy a baby carriage, and 35% buy a<br>car seat. No customer buys more than one of each item. If a customer buys both a baby<br>carriage and a car seat, the proprietor gives a 10% discount on the total.<br><br>Calculate the revenue the proprietor expects on a day that 200 people come to the store.<br><br>A) 8,200<br>B) 17,800<br>C) 18,400<br>D) 18,440<br>E) 29,800", "tags": ["ExamP::GeneralProbability"]},
    {"back": "<b>Answer: C) 0.167</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>Let iX be the number of claims for policyholder i. We have 1 () () . iiVar X E X= = The total<br>amount paid is then 1 1000100( )SX X= ++ \uf04c . Note that the solution employs the continuity<br>correction.<br>1 1000<br>22<br>1 1000<br>1/ 2<br>( ) 100[ ( ) ( )] 100(1, 000)(1) 100, 000<br>( ) 100 [ ( ) ( )] 100 (1, 000)(1) 10, 000, 000<br>( ) 10, 000, 000 3,162.28<br>Premium 1.03(100, 000) 103, 000<br>103, 050 100, 000( 103, 000) 3,<br>ES EX EX<br>Var S Var X Var X<br>StDev S<br>PS P Z<br>= ++ = =<br>= ++ = =<br>= =<br>= =<br>\u2212&gt;= &gt;<br>\uf04c<br>\uf04c<br>0.9645 0.167162.28<br>\uf8eb\uf8f6 = =\uf8ec\uf8f7\uf8ed\uf8f8<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q416. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "A company has 1000 dental insurance policies. The number of claims filed by a<br>policyholder during one year is a Poisson random variable with variance 1. The number<br>of claims filed by these policyholders are mutually independent.<br><br>The payment for each dental claim is 100 and the annual premium for each policy is<br>103% of the total expected claim payments for that policy.<br><br>Calculate the probability, using the normal approximation, that the total claim payments<br>on the 1000 policies exceeds the total premium collected.<br><br>A) 0.001<br>B) 0.159<br>C) 0.167<br>D) 0.488<br>E) 0.500", "tags": ["ExamP::UnivariateRV", "ExamP::UnivariateRV::DiscreteDistributions"]},
    {"back": "<b>Answer: B) 0.00115</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>This is a negative binomial distribution.<br><br>P(Second fatal crash occurs on the fourth save) =<br>223 (0.02) (0.98)1<br>\uf8eb\uf8f6<br>\uf8ec\uf8f7\uf8ed\uf8f8<br>= 0.001152.<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q417. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "On average, a certain word processing software program has a fatal crash once in every<br>50 instances of saving a document.<br><br>The instances of fatal crashes, while saving, are independent from one another.<br><br>Calculate the probability that the second fatal crash, while saving, occurs on the fourth<br>instance of saving a document.<br><br>A) 0.00038<br>B) 0.00115<br>C) 0.00230<br>D) 0.01882<br>E) 0.02000", "tags": ["ExamP::GeneralProbability", "ExamP::GeneralProbability::Independence"]},
    {"back": "<b>Answer: C) 0.151</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>Let M = # of accidents in first year, N = # of accidents in second year.<br>( 1, 1) 0.08(0.08)( 1, 1 | 2) ( 2) 0.9(0.02) 0.08(0.08) 0.02(0.9)<br>0.0064 0.1510.0424<br>PM NPM N M N PM N<br>= == = +== =+= + +<br>= =<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q418. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "A policyholder purchases car insurance for two years. In a given year, the policyholder&#x27;s<br>number of car accidents is zero with probability 0.9, exactly one with probability 0.08,<br>and exactly two with probability 0.02. The number of accidents in the first year is<br>independent of the number in the second.<br><br>Calculate the probability that the policyholder has one accident in each year, given that<br>the policyholder has a total of exactly two accidents.<br><br>A) 0.006<br>B) 0.042<br>C) 0.151<br>D) 0.262<br>E) 0.960", "tags": ["ExamP::GeneralProbability", "ExamP::GeneralProbability::ConditionalProbability"]},
    {"back": "<b>Answer: B) 0.17</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>X = amount of time (years) before repair is needed, which is uniform on [0, 5]<br><br>[ 4.5 | 2]<br>[ 4.5]<br>[ 2]<br>5 4.5<br>150 0.16752 6<br>50<br>PX X<br>PX<br>PX<br>&gt;&gt;<br>&gt;= &gt;<br>\u2212<br>\u2212= = =\u2212<br>\u2212<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q419. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "A customer purchases a lawnmower with a two-year warranty. The number of years<br>before the lawnmower needs a repair is uniformly distributed on [0, 5].<br><br>Calculate the probability that the lawnmower needs no repairs within 4.5 years after the<br>purchase, given that the lawnmower needs no repairs within the warranty period.<br><br>A) 0.10<br>B) 0.17<br>C) 0.44<br>D) 0.50<br>E) 0.60", "tags": ["ExamP::UnivariateRV", "ExamP::UnivariateRV::ContinuousDistributions"]},
    {"back": "<b>Answer: C) 0.3298</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>Using integration by parts<br>22 22 21 2 1<br>11<br>11<br>( 2 ) 3 2 0.329753.x xx xxe dx xe e dx e e e e e\u2212 \u2212 \u2212 \u2212\u2212 \u2212 \u2212 \u2212= \u2212 \u2212\u2212 =\u2212 + \u2212 = \u2212 + =\u222b\u222b<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q420. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "A scientist estimates the time (in tens of millions of years) before a major asteroid will hit<br>the earth using a random variable X with probability density function<br><br>, for 0()<br>0, otherwise.<br>xxe xfx<br>\u2212\uf8f1 &gt;= \uf8f2<br>\uf8f3<br><br><br>Calculate the probability that the next time the earth is hit by a major asteroid occurs<br>between 10 million and 20 million years from now.<br><br>A) 0.0005<br>B) 0.0867<br>C) 0.3298<br>D) 0.6702<br>E) 0.9995", "tags": ["ExamP::UnivariateRV", "ExamP::UnivariateRV::ContinuousDistributions"]},
    {"back": "<b>Answer: C) 8.10</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>Let X = lifetime of a television of this brand:<br><br>2/7/<br>/3.8953<br>0.5 [ 2.7] 1<br>2.7 / 0.6931<br>3.8953<br>0.875 [ ] 1<br>/ 3.8953 2.0794<br>8.10.<br>p<br>PX e<br>PX P e<br>p<br>p<br>\u03b2<br>\u03b2<br>\u03b2<br>\u2212<br>\u2212<br>=&lt;= \u2212<br>=<br>=<br>= &lt;= \u2212<br>=<br>=<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q421. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "The lifetimes of televisions of a certain model are exponentially distributed with a<br>median of 2.7 years.<br><br>Calculate the 87.5<br>th percentile of the lifetimes for these televisions.<br><br>A) 3.08<br>B) 4.73<br>C) 8.10<br>D) 10.80<br>E) 19.68", "tags": ["ExamP::UnivariateRV", "ExamP::UnivariateRV::ContinuousDistributions"]},
    {"back": "<b>Answer: A) 0.00</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>Since one of C or D is guaranteed to occur, and they are mutually exclusive:<br>[ ] [ ] [ ] D A P C A P A P\u2229 + \u2229 = so,<br>[ ] 20 . 0 50 . 0 75 . 0= \u2212 = \u2229D A P .<br>Then, since one of A and B is guaranteed to occur:<br>[ ] [ ] [ ] D B P D A P D P\u2229 + \u2229 =,<br>so [ ] 00 . 0 20 . 0 20 . 0= \u2212 = \u2229D B P<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q422. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "Events A and B are mutually exclusive, and at least one of A or B is certain to occur.<br>Events C and D are mutually exclusive, and at least one of C or D is certain to occur.<br><br>The following probabilities are known:<br><br>i) P[A] = 0.75<br>ii) P[D] = 0.20<br>iii) P[A \u2229 C] = 0.55<br><br>Calculate P[B \u2229 D].<br><br>A) 0.00<br>B) 0.05<br>C) 0.20<br>D) 0.25<br>E) 0.45", "tags": ["ExamP::GeneralProbability", "ExamP::GeneralProbability::SampleSpacesEvents"]},
    {"back": "<b>Answer: C) 1/6</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>We are given the following:<br><br>Overstated Didn&#x27;t overstate Row Total<br>Claimed at least 1000 0.45 0.70<br>Claimed less than 1000<br>Column Total 0.50<br><br>This gives<br><br>Overstated Didn&#x27;t overstate Row Total<br>Claimed at least 1000 0.45 0.25 0.70<br>Claimed less than 1000 0.05 0.25 0.30<br>Column Total 0.50 0.50 1.00<br><br>Then, P(Overstated | Less than 1000) = P(Overstated and Less than 1000)/P(Less than 1000) =<br>0.05/0.30 = 1/6.<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q423. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "A survey was conducted within the population of those who claim to have contributed to<br>charity during the previous year. Results indicate that 70% of this population claimed to<br>have contributed at least 1000, 50% overstated the value of their contributions, and 45%<br>did both.<br><br>Assume that the survey accurately represents the population.<br><br>Calculate the probability that a randomly selected person overstated the value of his<br>contribution, given that they claimed to have contributed less than 1000.<br><br>A) 1/20<br>B) 1/10<br>C) 1/6<br>D) 3/4<br>E) 5/6", "tags": ["ExamP::GeneralProbability", "ExamP::GeneralProbability::ConditionalProbability"]},
    {"back": "<b>Answer: E) 9.360</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>There are (<br>26C3)(3) = 7,800 ways to select the 3 distinct upper case letters and choose one for the<br>leading position of the password. For each of those ways, there are 4P2 = 12 ways to allocate the<br>other two letters among the 4 open positions. So there are 93,600 ways to allocate the letters.<br>For each, there are 10<br>2 ways to select and place the two digits in the remaining two open<br>positions. Thus, there are 9,360,000 possibilities.<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q424. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "A website requires a five-character password consisting of exactly three distinct<br>characters selected from the 26 upper-case letters of the alphabet and exactly two<br>characters, not necessarily distinct, selected from the ten digits. The password must begin<br>with one of the selected letters.<br><br>Calculate the maximum number of unique passwords, in millions, the site will<br>accommodate.<br><br>A) 3.120<br>B) 4.212<br>C) 4.680<br>D) 8.424<br>E) 9.360", "tags": ["ExamP::GeneralProbability"]},
    {"back": "<b>Answer: B) 1</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>Let X = number of fillings, which has a Poisson distribution with mean \u03bb<br>0<br>0.18 [ 0] 0!<br>1.7147<br>ePX e<br>\u03bb<br>\u03bb\u03bb<br>\u03bb<br>\u2212<br>\u2212= = = =<br>=<br><br>Since the mean is 1.7147, the mode will be 1 as it can be shown that when the mean is not a<br>whole number, the mode is the largest whole number less than the mean. When the mean is a<br>whole number, there are two modes, the mean and one less than the mean.<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q425. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "This year, the number of tooth fillings a policyholder undergoes is Poisson distributed.<br>The probability that the policyholder undergoes no tooth fillings this year is 0.18.<br><br>Calculate the mode of the number of tooth fillings the policyholder undergoes this year.<br><br>A) 0<br>B) 1<br>C) 2<br>D) 5<br>E) 6", "tags": ["ExamP::UnivariateRV", "ExamP::UnivariateRV::DiscreteDistributions"]},
