    {"back": "<b>Answer: A) 0.71</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>Let X be the profit from flood insurance and Y be the profit from fire insurance and let S = X + Y be the<br>total profit. Let \u00b5 and \u03c3 be the mean and standard deviation of X.<br>00[ 0] 0.67 0.44 0.44PX P Z \u00b5\u00b5 \u03c3\u00b5\u03c3\u03c3<br>\u2212\u2212\uf8ee\uf8f9&gt;= &gt; = \u21d2 = \u2212 \u21d2 =\uf8ef\uf8fa\uf8f0\uf8fb<br><br>S has a normal distribution with mean [ ] [] 3 4E X EY \u00b5\u00b5\u00b5+ = += and standard deviation<br>22( ) ( ) 9 10Var X Var Y \u03c3\u03c3 \u03c3+ =+= .<br>0 4 4(0.44 )[ 0] 0.56 0.71<br>10 10<br>PS P Z \u00b5\u03c3<br>\u03c3\u03c3<br>\u2212\u2212\uf8ee\uf8f9&gt;= &gt; = = \u2212 =\uf8ef\uf8fa\uf8f0\uf8fb<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q433. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "An insurance company sells flood and fire insurance. This year, the company\u2019s profit<br>from selling flood insurance is normally distributed, and its profit from selling fire<br>insurance is normally distributed with three times the mean and three times the standard<br>deviation as from flood insurance.<br><br>The profits from the two types of insurance are independent. The probability that the<br>company earns a positive profit from selling flood insurance this year is 0.67.<br><br>Calculate the probability that the insurance company earns an overall positive profit this<br>year.<br><br>A) 0.71<br>B) 0.73<br>C) 0.81<br>D) 0.92<br>E) 0.96", "tags": ["ExamP::GeneralProbability", "ExamP::GeneralProbability::Independence"]},
    {"back": "<b>Answer: D) 1.55</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>Let<br>jX = number of accidents occurring on the jth roller coaster, for j = 1, 2, which is Poisson<br>distributed with mean j\u03bb .<br>The probability that at least one accident occurs on roller coaster j equals<br>( )<br>0<br>1P 0 1 1 . 0!<br>j<br>jj<br>j<br>e<br>Xe<br>\u03bb<br>\u03bb\u03bb<br>\u2212<br>\u2212<br>\uf8ee\uf8f9\u2212= = \u2212 = \u2212\uf8f0\uf8fb<br>Since the probability that at least one accident occurs on the second roller coaster is twice that<br>for the first roller coaster, ( )<br>211 21\u2212\u2212\u2212=\u2212ee\u03bb\u03bb . Then<br>( ) ( )<br>21 1 0.5<br>22 1 ln 2 1 ln 2 1 1.546ee e e\u03bb\u03bb \u03bb\u03bb\u2212\u2212 \u2212 \u2212= \u2212 \u21d2 = \u2212 \u2212= \u2212 \u2212= .<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q434. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "An amusement park has two roller coasters. This year, the numbers of accidents<br>occurring on the first and second roller coasters are Poisson distributed with means<br>1 0.5\u03bb = and 2\u03bb , respectively. The probability that at least one accident occurs on the<br>second roller coaster is twice the probability for the first roller coaster.<br><br>Calculate 2\u03bb .<br><br>A) 1.00<br>B) 1.19<br>C) 1.23<br>D) 1.55<br>E) 2.00", "tags": ["ExamP::UnivariateRV", "ExamP::UnivariateRV::DiscreteDistributions"]},
    {"back": "<b>Answer: B) \u201326</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>Standard deviation equals 85 implies mean = 85.<br>Let M equal the median<br>/85<br>[ ] 0.5<br>0.5<br>ln 0.585<br>58.92<br>M<br>PX M<br>e<br>M<br>M<br>\u2212<br>&gt;=<br>=<br>\u2212 =<br>=<br><br>So median minus mean = 58.92 - 85 = \u201326.08<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q435. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "A large city police department is conducting an analysis of the annual number of car<br>accidents in the city. The department hires an actuary who models the annual number of<br>car accidents using an exponential distribution with a variance of 7225.<br><br>Calculate the median minus the mean of this distribution.<br><br>A) \u20132217<br>B) \u201326<br>C) 0<br>D) 26<br>E) 2217", "tags": ["ExamP::UnivariateRV", "ExamP::UnivariateRV::ContinuousDistributions"]},
    {"back": "<b>Answer: D) 0.61</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>The mean equals the standard deviation, so is also 1000. By the memoryless property of the<br>exponential distribution,<br>0.001 0.001 0.5<br>500<br>500<br>[ 1500 | 1000] [ 500] 0.001 0.6065.xxPX X PX e d x e e<br>\u221e \u221e\u2212 \u2212\u2212&gt; &gt; =&gt;= = \u2212 == \u222b<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q436. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "An insurance policy has been purchased for a windmill farm. The policy will pay to<br>compensate for the loss of revenue resulting from certain weather hazards that shut down<br>the farm. Each such loss is exponentially distributed with standard deviation 1000.<br><br>Calculate the probability that a random loss exceeds 1500 given that it exceeds the mean.<br><br>A) 0.22<br>B) 0.39<br>C) 0.50<br>D) 0.61<br>E) 0.78", "tags": ["ExamP::UnivariateRV", "ExamP::UnivariateRV::ContinuousDistributions"]},
    {"back": "<b>Answer: D) 0.028</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>P[exactly 2 injuries]<br>= P[1 or 2 injuries] + P[2 or 3 injuries] \u2013 P[at least 1 injury] + P[4 or more injuries]<br>= 0.25 + 0.036 \u2013 0.26 + 0.002<br>= 0.028<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q437. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "Data from a study shows the following about the number of injuries a football player<br>experiences in a year:<br><br>i) The probability is 0.250 that the player experiences 1 or 2 injuries.<br>ii) The probability is 0.036 that the player experiences 2 or 3 injuries.<br>iii) The probability is 0.260 that the player experiences at least 1 injury.<br>iv) The probability is 0.002 that the player experiences at least 4 injuries.<br><br>Calculate the probability that the football player experiences exactly 2 injuries this year.<br><br>A) 0.009<br>B) 0.014<br>C) 0.024<br>D) 0.028<br>E) 0.048", "tags": ["ExamP::GeneralProbability"]},
    {"back": "<b>Answer: E) 10/21</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>The event that the first 5 items fill the truck to its capacity is equivalent to the event that the first<br>5 items include 3 items of Type A and 2 items of Type B. This is a hypergeometric probability:<br>64<br>32 20(6) 10<br>10 252 21<br>5<br>\uf8eb \uf8f6\uf8eb \uf8f6<br>\uf8ec \uf8f7\uf8ec \uf8f7\uf8ed \uf8f8\uf8ed \uf8f8 = =\uf8eb\uf8f6<br>\uf8ec\uf8f7\uf8ed\uf8f8<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q438. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "A delivery truck, when filled to capacity, can carry only three items of Type A in addition<br>to only two items of Type B.<br><br>One day, six items of Type A and four items of Type B await delivery. The ten items are<br>brought to the loading dock one at a time in random order.<br><br>Calculate the probability that the first five items brought to the loading dock will fill the<br>delivery truck to capacity.<br><br>A) 1/210<br>B) 1/21<br>C) 1/10<br>D) 21/100<br>E) 10/21", "tags": ["ExamP::GeneralProbability"]},
    {"back": "<b>Answer: D) 0.9535</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>Let X and Y be the profits in years 1 and 2 respectively. Let S = X + Y be the total profit for the<br>two years.<br>222 2 2<br>00.8531 [ 0] / 1.05 /1.05<br>00.9192 [ 0] / 1.40 /1.40<br>[ ] 2 , ( ) (1/1.05 1/1.40 ), 1.1905<br>02[ 0] 1.68 0.95351.1905<br>XX<br>X<br>YX<br>Y<br>XY S<br>PX P Z<br>PY P Z<br>E S Var S<br>PS P Z<br>\u00b5 \u00b5\u03c3 \u03c3 \u00b5\u03c3<br>\u00b5 \u00b5\u03c3 \u03c3 \u00b5\u03c3<br>\u00b5\u00b5 \u00b5 \u03c3 \u03c3 \u00b5 \u03c3 \u00b5<br>\u00b5<br>\u00b5<br>\uf8ee\uf8f9 \u2212= &gt; = &gt; \u21d2\u2212 =\u2212 \u21d2 =\uf8ef\uf8fa\uf8f0\uf8fb<br>\uf8ee\uf8f9 \u2212= &gt; = &gt; \u21d2\u2212 =\u2212 \u21d2 =\uf8ef\uf8fa<br>\uf8f0\uf8fb<br>=+= = + = + =<br>\uf8ee\uf8f9 \u2212&gt;= &gt; = \u2212 =\uf8ef\uf8fa\uf8f0\uf8fb<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q439. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "An insurance company\u2019s profit for one year is normally distributed with probability<br>0.8531 of being positive.<br><br>The company\u2019s profit the next year is normally distributed with probability 0.9192 of<br>being positive.<br><br>The yearly profits are independent with the same mean but different standard deviations.<br><br>Calculate the probability that the insurance company earns an overall positive profit in<br>this two-year period.<br><br>A) 0.7842<br>B) 0.7995<br>C) 0.8849<br>D) 0.9535<br>E) 0.9929", "tags": ["ExamP::GeneralProbability", "ExamP::GeneralProbability::Independence"]},
    {"back": "<b>Answer: E) 577</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>The distribution function for an exponential distribution is<br>/() 1 xFx e \u03bb\u2212= \u2212 .<br>400/<br>400/<br>1 0.5<br>0.5<br>400/ ln0.5<br>577.08.<br>e<br>e<br>\u03bb<br>\u03bb<br>\u03bb<br>\u03bb<br>\u2212<br>\u2212<br>\u2212=<br>=<br>\u2212=<br>=<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q440. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "Losses under a boat insurance policy are exponentially distributed. The median loss is<br>400.<br><br>Calculate the mean loss.<br><br>A) 400<br>B) 446<br>C) 492<br>D) 533<br>E) 577", "tags": ["ExamP::UnivariateRV", "ExamP::UnivariateRV::ContinuousDistributions"]},
