    {"back": "<b>Answer: C) 1.42</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>Let X represent the amount of time (in years) between now and the first ticket.<br>Let Y represent the amount of time (in years) between the first ticket and the second ticket.<br>X and Y are independent and exponentially distributed with means 0.8 and \u03bc &gt; 0.8, respectively.<br><br>The variance of an exponential distribution is the square of its mean, and the variance of a sum<br>of independent random variables is the sum of the variances. Therefore, the variance of the<br>number of years from now to the second ticket is<br>222.65 ( ) ( ) ( ) 0.8Var X Y Var X Var Y \u00b5= += + = + . Thus, 22.65 (0.8) 1.418.\u00b5 =\u2212= .<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q474. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "A motorist currently has no traffic tickets.<br><br>The amount of time between now and when the motorist receives the first ticket is<br>exponentially distributed with mean 0.80 years.<br><br>The motorist plans to drive more carefully after receiving the first ticket. Hence the mean<br>time from the first ticket to the second is greater than 0.80. The amount of time between<br>the first ticket and the second ticket is exponentially distributed and is independent of<br>when the motorist receives the first ticket.<br><br>The variance of the number of years from now until the second ticket is 2.65.<br><br>Calculate the expected amount of time, in years, between the motorist&#x27;s first and second<br>traffic tickets.<br><br>A) 0.83<br>B) 0.96<br>C) 1.42<br>D) 1.85<br>E) 2.01", "tags": ["ExamP::UnivariateRV", "ExamP::UnivariateRV::ContinuousDistributions"]},
