    {"back": "<b>Answer: D) 0.21</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>Add the probabilities for number of deaths less than 2. Add the probabilities for number of<br>deaths less than 2 and number of disabilities at least 2. Divide second sum by first sum.<br>0.18 0.20930.0.86 =<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q476. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "An insurer sells an annual group life and disability policy.<br><br>The joint probability distribution for death and disability is:<br><br><br>Annual Number of Deaths<br>0 1 2 3 4<br>Annual<br>Number of<br>Disabilities<br>0 0.45 0.09 0.03 0.01 0.01<br>1 0.08 0.06 0.02 0.01 0.01<br>2 0.07 0.05 0.02 0.01 0.00<br>3 0.04 0.02 0.01 0.01 0.00<br><br>Calculate the probability of at least two disabilities, given no more than one death.<br><br>A) 0.14<br>B) 0.17<br>C) 0.18<br>D) 0.21<br>E) 0.32", "tags": ["ExamP::MultivariateRV", "ExamP::MultivariateRV::JointDistributions"]},
    {"back": "<b>Answer: B) 0.20</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>[ 10 | 5] P[5 10] / P[ 5]PT T T T\u2264 \u2265= \u2264\u2264 \u2264<br>10 102<br>55<br>20 202<br>55<br>75 0.20375<br>ktdt t<br>tktdt<br>= = =\u222b<br>\u222b<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q477. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "The time, in years, until replacement for a new telephone pole has probability density<br>function<br><br><br>, for 0 20() 0, otherwise,<br>kt tft &lt;&lt;\uf8f1=\uf8f2<br>\uf8f3<br><br><br>where k is a constant.<br><br>Calculate the probability that a new telephone pole will be replaced within ten years<br>given that it is not replaced within five years.<br><br>A) 0.19<br>B) 0.20<br>C) 0.25<br>D) 0.33<br>E) 0.94", "tags": ["ExamP::GeneralProbability", "ExamP::GeneralProbability::ConditionalProbability"]},
    {"back": "<b>Answer: B) 5.5</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>The variance of the sum of independent random variables is the sum of the individual variances.<br>So the variance of the total health insurance cost is 1<br>2 + 22 + 32 + 42 = 30 . The standard<br>deviation of the total cost is the square root: 30 5.4772.=<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q478. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "A company provides health insurance to employees located at four different plants.<br>Health insurance costs at each plant are independent of those costs at any other plant.<br>Plant managers have calculated the following statistics:<br><br>Plant<br>Average<br>Cost<br>Standard<br>Deviation<br>1<br>2<br>3<br>4<br>2<br>2<br>5<br>7<br>1<br>2<br>3<br>4<br><br>Calculate the standard deviation of the total company health insurance costs.<br><br>A) 2.5<br>B) 5.5<br>C) 7.5<br>D) 10.0<br>E) 12.5", "tags": ["ExamP::GeneralProbability", "ExamP::GeneralProbability::Independence"]},
    {"back": "<b>Answer: D) 15.6</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>The variance of a uniform distribution is<br>1<br>12<br>of the square of the interval length. For the<br>hospitalization charge: 43<br>12<br>c = , so that c = 24.<br>The standard deviation of the surgery charge is 3 18 3(24) 18 54 15.5885.<br>12 12 12<br>c\u2212\u2212 \uf8eb\uf8f6= = =\uf8ec\uf8f7\uf8ed\uf8f8<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q479. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "A patient must undergo hospitalization and surgery. The hospitalization and surgery<br>charges are modeled by random variables uniformly distributed on the intervals [0, ]c<br>and [0, 3 18]c\u2212 , respectively, where c is a constant larger than 6.<br><br>The standard deviation of the hospitalization charge is 43 .<br><br>Calculate the standard deviation of the surgery charge.<br><br>A) 2.8<br>B) 7.3<br>C) 10.4<br>D) 15.6<br>E) 20.8", "tags": ["ExamP::UnivariateRV", "ExamP::UnivariateRV::ContinuousDistributions"]},
    {"back": "<b>Answer: C) 37.79</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>For one policyholder<br>2<br>2<br>( ) 0.8(0) 0.16(1) 0.04(2) 0.24<br>( ) 0.08(0) 0.16(1) 0.04(4) 0.32<br>( ) 0.32 0.24 0.2624.<br>EX<br>EX<br>Var X<br>= ++=<br>=++=<br>= \u2212=<br><br>Because they are independent, the variance of the sum is the sum of the variances: 144(0.2624) =<br>37.7856.<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q480. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "In a group of 144 car insurance policyholders, each policyholder has no accidents this<br>year with probability 0.80, one accident with probability 0.16, and two accidents with<br>probability 0.04.<br><br>The numbers of accidents this year for different policyholders are mutually independent.<br><br>Calculate the variance of the total number of accidents this year for this group of<br>policyholders.<br><br>A) 3.15<br>B) 34.56<br>C) 37.79<br>D) 46.08<br>E) 54.37", "tags": ["ExamP::GeneralProbability", "ExamP::GeneralProbability::Independence"]},
    {"back": "<b>Answer: E) 15</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>Each value has probability 0.2.<br>2<br>22<br>( ) 1(0.2) 2(0.2) 3(0.2) 4(0.2) 5(0.2) 3<br>( ) 1(0.2) 4(0.2) 9(0.2) 16(0.2) 25(0.2) 11<br>(Cost) ( 1) ( ) ( ) 1 11 3 1 15.<br>EN<br>EN<br>E EN N EN EN<br>=++++=<br>=+++ + =<br>= + + = + += ++=<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q481. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "The number of days required for a damage control team to locate and repair a leak in the<br>hull of a ship is modeled by a discrete random variable, N. N is uniformly distributed on<br>{1, 2, 3, 4, 5}.<br><br>The cost of locating and repairing a leak is<br>2 1.NN++<br><br>Calculate the expected cost of locating and repairing a leak in the hull of the ship.<br><br>A) 11<br>B) 12<br>C) 13<br>D) 14<br>E) 15", "tags": ["ExamP::UnivariateRV", "ExamP::UnivariateRV::DiscreteDistributions"]},
    {"back": "<b>Answer: B) 1.27</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>2<br>2<br>2<br>() 3 2<br>6<br>6<br>()() 1 1 12<br>(6 ) 112<br>1.26795.<br>abEX<br>ab<br>ba<br>baVX<br>aa<br>a<br>+= =<br>+<br>=<br>= \u2212<br>\u2212= = =<br>\u2212\u2212 =<br>=<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q482. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "A flight is delayed due to bad weather. The delay time is modeled by a random variable<br>with a continuous uniform distribution. The expected delay time is three hours, and the<br>standard deviation of the delay time is one hour.<br><br>Calculate the shortest possible delay time, in hours.<br><br>A) 0.58<br>B) 1.27<br>C) 1.73<br>D) 2.31<br>E) 2.42", "tags": ["ExamP::UnivariateRV", "ExamP::UnivariateRV::ContinuousDistributions"]},
    {"back": "<b>Answer: A) 15.39</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>The number who test positive for disease A has a binomial distribution with n = 100 and p. Then<br>9 = 100p(1 \u2013 p) which implies that p = 0.1 (0.9 is also a solution but we are given that p is<br>between 0 and 0,5.<br><br>The probability of having at least one disease is 1 minus the probability of neither having the<br>disease. Thus, this probability is 1 \u2013 0.9(0.9) = 0.19. The variance for 100 patients is<br>100(0.19)(0.81) = 15.29.<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q483. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "A doctor tests 100 patients for two diseases, A and B. Each patient has probability p of<br>having disease A and probability p of having disease B, with<br>0 0.50\u2264\u2264p .<br><br>For each patient, the event of having disease A and the event of having disease B are<br>independent. The test outcomes for different patients are mutually independent.<br><br>The variance of the number of patients who have disease A is 9.00.<br><br>Calculate the variance of the number of patients who have at least one of the two<br>diseases.<br><br>A) 15.39<br>B) 1600<br>C) 16.59<br>D) 17.19<br>E) 18.00", "tags": ["ExamP::GeneralProbability", "ExamP::GeneralProbability::Independence"]},
    {"back": "<b>Answer: B) 17.5</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>The 40th percentile for Denver is at 0.6(25) + 0.4(90) = 51.<br>The 20th percentile for Philadelphia is at 0.8(45) + 0.2x = 36 + 0.2x.<br>Equating them yields x = 75.<br>Therefore, Salt Lake City salaries are uniform from 10 to 25 and the median is (10 + 25)/2 =<br>17.5.<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q484. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "An insurance company has customer service operations in Denver, Philadelphia, and Salt<br>Lake City.<br><br>Employee salaries in Denver are uniformly distributed from 25 to 90. Employee salaries<br>in Philadelphia are uniformly distributed from 45 to x. Employee salaries in Salt Lake<br>City are uniformly distributed from 10 to x/3.<br><br>The 40<br>th percentile of Denver salaries is equal to the 20th percentile of Philadelphia<br>salaries.<br><br>Calculate the median of Salt Lake City employee salaries.<br><br>A) 12.5<br>B) 17.5<br>C) 25.0<br>D) 35.0<br>E) 60.0", "tags": ["ExamP::UnivariateRV", "ExamP::UnivariateRV::ContinuousDistributions"]},
    {"back": "<b>Answer: B) 58.7</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>The 40<br>th percentile is at 0.6a + 0.4(2a) = 1.4a.<br>The 80th percentile is at 0.2a + 0.8(2a) = 1.8a.<br>The pth percentile (treating p is a decimal) is at (1 \u2013 p)a + p(2a) = a + pa = (1 + p)a.<br>Then,<br>2<br>1.4 (1 )<br>(1 ) 1.8<br>1.4(1.8) (1 )<br>1.58745 1<br>0.58745 58.7%.<br>a pa<br>pa a<br>p<br>p<br>p<br>+=+<br>= +<br>= +<br>= =<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q485. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "The loss due to a warehouse robbery is modeled by a uniform distribution on the interval<br>[ ],2aa , where a is a positive constant.<br><br>The ratio of the 40<br>th percentile of the loss to the pth percentile of the loss equals the ratio<br>of the pth percentile of the loss to the 80th percentile of the loss.<br><br>Calculate p.<br><br>A) 56.6<br>B) 58.7<br>C) 60.0<br>D) 61.4<br>E) 65.4", "tags": ["ExamP::UnivariateRV", "ExamP::UnivariateRV::ContinuousDistributions"]},
    {"back": "<b>Answer: B) 0.488</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>The number of such claims, N, is binomial with n = 3 and p = 0.2.<br><br>3( 0) 1 ( 0) 1 0.8 0.488PN PN&gt;= \u2212 == \u2212 =<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q486. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "A study of fire damage claims is conducted. Claim amounts are mutually independent<br>and each claim amount exceeds 1000 with probability 0.20.<br><br>Calculate the probability that at least one of three randomly selected claim amounts<br>exceeds 1000.<br><br>A) 0.472<br>B) 0.488<br>C) 0.512<br>D) 0.528<br>E) 0.600", "tags": ["ExamP::GeneralProbability", "ExamP::GeneralProbability::Independence"]},
    {"back": "<b>Answer: B) 0.19</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>The denominator is the probability of not passing all three exams, which is 1 \u2013 0.36 = 0.64. The<br>numerator is the probability of passing Exam 2 and not passing Exam 3. This is 0.48 \u2013 0.36 =<br>0.12. The desired conditional probability is 0.12/0.64 = 0.1875.<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q487. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "A group of students will take Exam 1. Those who pass Exam 1 will take Exam 2. Those<br>who also pass Exam 2 will take Exam 3. For the initial group, the probability of passing<br>Exam 1 is 0.80, the probability of passing Exams 1 and 2 is 0.48, and the probability of<br>passing Exams 1, 2, and 3 is 0.36. A student who fails an exam stops taking exams.<br><br>Calculate the probability that a student of this group passes Exam 2, given that the<br>student does not pass all three exams.<br><br>A) 0.12<br>B) 0.19<br>C) 0.25<br>D) 0.64<br>E) 0.75", "tags": ["ExamP::GeneralProbability", "ExamP::GeneralProbability::ConditionalProbability"]},
    {"back": "<b>Answer: B) 0.08</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>Let N denote the number of the phone call that produced the third completed survey. For N = 8,<br>the preceding seven surveys must produce exactly two completed surveys. This is a binomial<br>probability,<br>257 (0.25) (0.75) 0.31146.2<br>\uf8eb\uf8f6 =\uf8ec\uf8f7\uf8ed\uf8f8<br>The eighth call must result in a completed survey, so<br>the total probability is 0.31146(0.25) = 0.078. A direct solution can be obtained by recognizing<br>this is a negative binomial random variable and remembering the probability function.<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q488. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "A representative of a market research firm contacts consumers by phone to conduct<br>surveys. The specific consumer contacted by each phone call is randomly determined.<br>The probability that a phone call produces a completed survey is 0.25.<br>Calculate the probability that the eighth phone call produces the third completed survey.<br><br>A) 0.03<br>B) 0.08<br>C) 0.13<br>D) 0.21<br>E) 0.31", "tags": ["ExamP::GeneralProbability"]},
    {"back": "<b>Answer: C) 40</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>Let b = maximum benefit. Then,<br>22 260<br>10<br>2<br>2<br>10 60 120 10031 / 50 / 50 100 50 100<br>3100 120 100<br>120 3200 0<br>( 40)( 80) 0.<br>b<br>b<br>b bb bx dx b dx b<br>bb<br>bb<br>bb<br>\u2212 \u2212 \u2212+ \u2212= + =+=<br>= \u2212+ \u2212<br>\u2212+=<br>\u2212 \u2212=<br>\u222b\u222b<br><br>The only feasible solution is b = 40.<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q489. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "The amount of loss under an insurance policy is uniformly distributed on [10, 60]. The<br>insurer will reimburse the full amount of the loss up to a maximum benefit. The expected<br>benefit per loss is equal to 31.<br><br>Calculate the maximum benefit under the policy.<br><br>A) 35<br>B) 38<br>C) 40<br>D) 52<br>E) 56", "tags": ["ExamP::UnivariateRV", "ExamP::UnivariateRV::ContinuousDistributions"]},
    {"back": "<b>Answer: D) 0.336</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>Let X = # of fragile packages that break; Y = # of non-fragile packages that break. For the<br>denominator,<br>P(X + Y = 2) = P(X = 2)P(Y = 0) + P(X = 1)P(Y = 1) + P(X = 0)(Y = 2)<br>= [(0.2)(0.2)][(0.9)(0.9)] + [2(0.8)(0.2)][2(0.1)(0.9)] + [(0.8)(0.8)][(0.1)(0.1)] = 0.0964.<br>For the numerator,<br>P(X = 2 and X + Y = 2) = P(X = 2 and Y = 0) = (0.2)(0.2)(0.9)(0.9) = 0.0324.<br>The conditional probability is 0.0324/0.0964 = 0.336.<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q490. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "A person mails four packages. Two are fragile and two are not.<br><br>Each fragile package has probability 0.2 of breaking; each non-fragile package has<br>probability 0.1 of breaking. The occurrences of packages breaking are mutually<br>independent.<br><br>Exactly two packages break.<br><br>Calculate the probability that both broken packages were fragile.<br><br>A) 0.032<br>B) 0.040<br>C) 0.167<br>D) 0.336<br>E) 0.609", "tags": ["ExamP::GeneralProbability", "ExamP::GeneralProbability::Independence"]},
