    {"back": "<b>Answer: A) 0.27</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>Let A be the event that the fire policy is purchased and B be the event that the flood policy is<br>purchased. Also let x be the probability that neither is purchased:<br>1 P( ) 0.2 P( ), so P( ) 0.2.x AB AB AB x= \u2212 \u222a=+ \u2229 \u2229= \u2212<br>First from statement iii): ( ) ( )<br>( ) ( ) ( )<br>( )<br>22PA B PA BP AB P BAPB PA<br>\u2229\u2229= = = .<br>From the second and fourth expressions in the above line we get ( ) ( )1<br>2PB PA= , since<br>( ) 0PA B\u2229\u2260 .<br>Now, ( ) ( ) ( ) ( )PA B PA PB PA B\u222a= + \u2212 \u2229 .Substituting, we get<br>( ) ( ) ( )11 0.22x PA PA x\u2212= + \u2212 \u2212 , and so ( )31 0.2 2 PA\u2212= . Thus ( ) ( )280.83 15PA = = , and<br>( ) ( )14 0.26662 15PB PA= = = .<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q528. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "An actuary makes the following observations about an insurer\u2019s fire and flood<br>insurance policies:<br><br>i) The probability that a client purchases neither policy exceeds the<br>probability that a client purchases both policies by 0.20.<br><br>ii) The probability that a client purchases both policies is positive.<br><br>iii) The probability that a client purchases a fire policy given that the client<br>purchases a flood policy is twice the probability that a client purchases a<br>flood policy given that the client purchases a fire policy.<br><br>Calculate the probability that a client purchases a flood policy.<br><br>A) 0.27<br>B) 0.33<br>C) 0.40<br>D) 0.53<br>E) 0.80", "tags": ["ExamP::GeneralProbability", "ExamP::GeneralProbability::ConditionalProbability"]},
    {"back": "<b>Answer: B) 0.09</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>This is a Poisson Random Variable. with \u03bb= 0.25. Since we are talking about two applications,<br>0.5 0 0.5 1<br>P( 1) 1 (0) (1)<br>(0.5) (0.5)1 0! 1!<br>1 0.6065 0.3033<br>0.0902.<br>x pp<br>ee\u2212\u2212<br>&gt;= \u2212 \u2212<br>= \u2212\u2212<br>= \u2212\u2212<br>=<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q529. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "The number of errors on an application is modeled by a Poisson random variable with<br>variance 0.25.<br><br>The number of errors on any application is independent of the number of errors on all<br>other applications.<br><br>Calculate the probability that two applications contain a total of more than one error.<br><br>A) 0.03<br>B) 0.09<br>C) 0.30<br>D) 0.61<br>E) 0.91", "tags": ["ExamP::UnivariateRV", "ExamP::UnivariateRV::DiscreteDistributions"]},
    {"back": "<b>Answer: C) 0.074</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>Label the three dice, A, B, and C in the order presented.<br>If A and B are selected, an 11 can be obtained only with a 5 from A and a 6 from B. The<br>probability is (1/6)(1/3) = 1/18<br>If A and C are selected, an 11 can be obtained only with a 5 from A and a 6 from C. The<br>probability is (1/6)(1) = 1/6.<br>If B and C are selected, an 11 is not possible.<br>The total probability is (1/3)(1/18) + (1/3)(1/6) = 4/54 = 0.0741.<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q530. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "A box contains three fair dice. One has faces numbered 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, and 6; one has faces<br>numbered 2, 2, 4, 4, 6, and 6; and one has all six faces numbered 6. Two of the three dice<br>are randomly selected and rolled.<br><br>Calculate the probability that the sum of the numbers rolled on the two dice is 11.<br><br>A) 0.025<br>B) 0.028<br>C) 0.074<br>D) 0.111<br>E) 0.222", "tags": ["ExamP::GeneralProbability"]},
    {"back": "<b>Answer: D) 0.03</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>Assuming independence:<br>( ) ( )<br>P( ) 0.10(0.30) 0.03<br>1 P( ) P( ) P( ) 1 0.10 0.30 0.03 0.63.<br>FT<br>p F T FT<br>\u2229= =<br>= \u2212 + \u2212 \u2229= \u2212 + \u2212 =<br>Assuming mutually exclusive:<br>1 P( ) P( ) 1 0.10 0.30 0.60r FT= \u2212 \u2212= \u2212\u2212=<br>0.63 0.60 0.03.pr\u2212= \u2212 =<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q531. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "A policyholder is insured against both fire and theft claims. The probability of a fire<br>claim is 10%. The probability of a theft claim is 30%.<br><br>Let p be the probability of having neither a fire nor a theft claim, assuming fire and theft<br>claims are independent.<br><br>Let r be the probability of having neither a fire nor a theft claim, assuming fire and theft<br>claims are mutually exclusive.<br><br>Calculate p \u2013 r.<br><br>A) \u22120.06<br>B) \u22120.03<br>C) 0.00<br>D) 0.03<br>E) 0.06", "tags": ["ExamP::GeneralProbability", "ExamP::GeneralProbability::SampleSpacesEvents"]},
    {"back": "<b>Answer: D) 0.48</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>P( ) 0.05, P( ) 0.80<br>P( ) P( )P( | ) 0.03 P( ) 0.024.P( ) 0.80<br>F FDIC<br>F FDIC F FDICF FDIC F FDICFDIC<br>= =<br>\u2229\u2229== = \u21d2\u2229 =<br>We want: P( ) 0.024P( | ) 0.48.P( ) 0.05<br>F FDICFDIC F F<br>\u2229= = =<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q532. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "In a certain region, 5% of all banks will fail in the next five years. The FDIC insures<br>80% of the banks in the region. Only 3% of the banks in the region insured by the FDIC<br>will fail in the next five years.<br><br>Calculate the probability that a bank in the region that fails in the next five years is<br>insured by the FDIC.<br><br>A) 0.02<br>B) 0.04<br>C) 0.06<br>D) 0.48<br>E) 0.60", "tags": ["ExamP::GeneralProbability"]},
    {"back": "<b>Answer: E) 0.833</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>Since all employees are independent and have the same accident risk, all combinations of three<br>employees with accidents are equally likely. Therefore,<br><br>P[at least 1 accident in dept. B] = 1 \u2013 P[the 3 &quot;accident&quot; employees are all in dept. A]:<br>64<br>30 20 1 51 1 0.8333.10 120 6<br>3<br>\uf8eb \uf8f6\uf8eb \uf8f6<br>\uf8ec \uf8f7\uf8ec \uf8f7 \u00d7\uf8ed \uf8f8\uf8ed \uf8f8\u2212 = \u2212= =\uf8eb\uf8f6<br>\uf8ec\uf8f7\uf8ed\uf8f8<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q533. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "This year, each of the ten employees of a company has probability 0.2 of having at least<br>one accident. The occurrences of accidents among different employees are mutually<br>independent.<br><br>Of the ten employees, six are in department A. The other four are in department B.<br><br>Exactly three of the ten employees each have at least one accident.<br><br>Calculate the probability that at least one of these accidents occurs to an employee in<br>department B.<br><br>A) 0.201<br>B) 0.500<br>C) 0.590<br>D) 0.784<br>E) 0.833", "tags": ["ExamP::GeneralProbability", "ExamP::GeneralProbability::Independence"]},
    {"back": "<b>Answer: C) 0.0705</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>P[at least 1 accident during a given year] =<br>0.10 0<br>0.100.101 P[0] 1 1 .0!<br>e e<br>\u2212<br>\u2212\u2212= \u2212 = \u2212<br>P[first accident in sixth year | no accidents in first two years]<br>= P[first accident in sixth year and no accidents in first two years] / P[no accidents in first two<br>years]<br>= P[first accident in sixth year]/ P[no accidents in first two years]<br>5<br>2<br>P[0] P[ 1] ,P[0]<br>\u2265= by independence.<br>( ) ( )<br>( )<br>50.10 0.10<br>20.10<br>1<br>0.070498.<br>ee<br>e<br>\u2212\u2212<br>\u2212<br>\u2212<br>=<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q534. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "In a given year, the number of accidents an auto insurance policyholder experiences is<br>Poisson distributed with mean 0.10. The numbers of accidents by year are independent.<br><br>Calculate the probability that a policyholder&#x27;s first accident occurs during the sixth year<br>of the policy, given that the policyholder experiences no accidents during the first two<br>years of the policy.<br><br>A) 0.0009<br>B) 0.0577<br>C) 0.0705<br>D) 0.0729<br>E) 0.3297", "tags": ["ExamP::GeneralProbability", "ExamP::GeneralProbability::ConditionalProbability"]},
    {"back": "<b>Answer: A) 1,700</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>Let:<br>X<br>= loss under health insurance policy<br>Y = loss under dental insurance policy<br>Var(X) = 40,000; Var(Y) = 10,000; X and Y are independent<br>U = total unreimbursed loss = 0.2X + 0.1Y<br>22<br>22<br>Var( ) Var(0.2 0.1 )<br>Var(0.2 ) Var(0.1 ), since independent<br>=0.2 Var( ) 0.1 Var( )<br>0.2 (40,000) 0.1 (10,000)<br>1700.<br>U XY<br>XY<br>XY<br>= +<br>= +<br>+<br>= +<br>=<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q535. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "A policyholder experiences one accident under a health insurance policy and one accident<br>under a dental insurance policy. The health insurance policy reimburses 80% of losses.<br>Losses under this policy have variance 40,000. The dental insurance policy reimburses<br>90% of losses. Losses under this policy have variance 10,000.<br><br>The policyholder&#x27;s two losses are independent.<br><br>Calculate the variance of the policyholder&#x27;s total unreimbursed loss under these policies.<br><br>A) 1,700<br>B) 9,000<br>C) 16,300<br>D) 33,700<br>E) 50,000", "tags": ["ExamP::GeneralProbability", "ExamP::GeneralProbability::Independence"]},
    {"back": "<b>Answer: C) 2.10</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>( ) ( 5) 0.3<br>( ) ( 5 or 6) 0.3 0.7 1.0<br>( ) ( 4 or 6) 0.1 0.7 0.8<br>0.3 1.0 0.8 2.1<br>PA B P<br>PA C P<br>PB C P<br>\u222a=&lt;=<br>\u222a=&lt; =+=<br>\u222a=&lt; =+=<br>++=<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q536. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "A weighted six-sided die is rolled. Let A be the event that the number rolled is less than<br>5. Let B be the event that the number rolled is less than 4. Let C be the event that the<br>number rolled is a 6. The probabilities of A, B, and C are 0.3, 0.1, and 0.7, respectively.<br><br>Calculate P[A<br>\u222aB] + P[A\u222aC] + P[B\u222aC].<br><br>A) 1.10<br>B) 1.89<br>C) 2.10<br>D) 2.17<br>E) 2.20", "tags": ["ExamP::GeneralProbability"]},
    {"back": "<b>Answer: C) 0.240</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>In a given year, the probability of evacuating is the probability of evacuating given there is at<br>least one hurricane times the probability of at least one hurricane, 0.35(0.25) = 0.0875.<br>The probability of never evacuating in three years is 0.9125<br>3 = 0.7598.<br>The probability of being evacuated at least once is 1 \u2013 0.7598 = 0.2402.<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q537. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "An actuary accepts an assignment to live and work in Key West, Florida for three years.<br><br>The probability that there are no hurricanes in Key West is 0.75 per year. If there is at<br>least one hurricane in Key West in a year, then the probability is 0.35 that the actuary will<br>need to evacuate in that year. There is no other reason for the actuary to evacuate.<br><br>The year-to-year occurrences of hurricanes in Key West are independent events.<br><br>Calculate the probability that the actuary will need to evacuate at least once from Key<br>West before the assignment is complete.<br><br>A) 0.088<br>B) 0.219<br>C) 0.240<br>D) 0.422<br>E) 0.578", "tags": ["ExamP::GeneralProbability", "ExamP::GeneralProbability::Independence"]},
    {"back": "<b>Answer: A) 1</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>Let X = number of tests; X is geometric with success probability p = 0.0625;<br>1[ ] (1 0.0625) (0.0625)nPX n \u2212= = \u2212 for all values of 1.n\u2265<br>P[X = n] is maximized when the exponent n - 1 is minimized, which occurs at n = 1. The mode<br>of X is 1.<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q538. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "Each person in a certain large population independently has probability 0.0625 of having<br>a certain disease. People in this population are tested for the disease, until somebody is<br>found to have the disease.<br><br>Calculate the mode of the number of people tested.<br><br>A) 1<br>B) 6<br>C) 11<br>D) 15<br>E) 16", "tags": ["ExamP::GeneralProbability"]},
