    {"back": "<b>Answer: A) 0.01</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>The expected number of accidents for a single driver is 0.16.<br>The expected number of accidents for 40,000 drivers is 40,000(0.16) = 6,400<br>The variance of the number of accidents for a single driver is 0.16.<br>The variance of the number of accidents for 40,000 drivers is 40.000(0.16) = 6,400 (the variance<br>of the sum of independent random variables is the sum of their variances).<br>6400CV( ) 0.0125.6400X = =<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q573. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "A company insures 40,000 drivers. The annual number of auto accidents for individual<br>drivers is modeled by mutually independent Poisson random variables with mean 0.16.<br><br>Calculate the coefficient of variation for the total annual number of auto accidents for all<br>40,000 drivers.<br><br>A) 0.01<br>B) 0.16<br>C) 0.40<br>D) 1.00<br>E) 2.50", "tags": ["ExamP::UnivariateRV", "ExamP::UnivariateRV::DiscreteDistributions"]},
