    {"back": "<b>Answer: D) 0.1110</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>Let<br>rX denote the trial on which the thr success occurs in a sequence of Bernoulli trials. Then<br>rX has the negative binomial distribution:<br>[ ] ( )<br>1<br>1<br>P 1 , , 1, 2,...<br>x xrr<br>r r<br>X x p p where x r r r<br>\u2212 \u2212<br>\u2212<br>\uf8eb\uf8f6== \u2212 =++\uf8ec\uf8f7\uf8ed\uf8f8<br><br>2212<br>2<br>10<br>1 37P[10 12] 0.0467 0.0363 0.0280 0.1110.1 10 10<br>x<br>x<br>xX<br>\u2212<br>=<br>\u2212\uf8eb\uf8f6 \uf8eb\uf8f6 \uf8eb\uf8f6\u2264\u2264= = + + =\uf8ec\uf8f7 \uf8ec\uf8f7 \uf8ec\uf8f7\uf8ed\uf8f8<br>\uf8ed\uf8f8\uf8ed\uf8f8\u2211<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q659. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "Rangers at a mountain resort set explosives to detonate at various locations to induce a<br>controlled avalanche after a snowfall. A controlled avalanche will start after two<br>effective detonations, and the probability that a detonation will be effective is 0.30.<br>Assume the effectiveness of different detonations are independent.<br><br>Calculate the probability that the second effective detonation will occur from the tenth to<br>twelfth detonations inclusive.<br><br>A) 0.0280<br>B) 0.0363<br>C) 0.0856<br>D) 0.1110<br>E) 0.1223", "tags": ["ExamP::GeneralProbability", "ExamP::GeneralProbability::Independence"]},
    {"back": "<b>Answer: B) e\u20131</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>Let X = number of months until the motorist is charged, which is exponentially distributed with<br>parameter<br>1 0.42.5\u03bb = = . We want to find<br>1 2.5 12.5( 2.5) .PX e e<br>\u2212 \u2212&gt;= =<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q660. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "A motorist decides not to renew a car insurance policy. The number of months until the<br>motorist is charged for driving without insurance is exponentially distributed with mean<br>2.50.<br><br>Calculate the probability that the motorist lasts at least 2.50 months without being charged.<br><br>A) 1 \u2013 e<br>\u20130.4<br>B) e\u20131<br>C) 1 \u2013 e \u20131<br>D) e\u20130.4<br>E) 1 \u2013 e \u20136.25", "tags": ["ExamP::UnivariateRV", "ExamP::UnivariateRV::ContinuousDistributions"]},
    {"back": "<b>Answer: A) 0.0466</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>Let X = number of buildings in the group damaged by high tides<br>We want to find P[at least one damaged | at least one undamaged]<br>P[1 3] 0.015 0.01 0.02 9P[ 1| 3] 0.0466.P[ 3] 0.92 0.015 0.01 0.02 193<br>XXX X<br>\u2264\u2264 + +\u2265 \u2264= = = =\u2264 + ++<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q661. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "A group of four buildings are near each other on a coastline. A statistician models the<br>probability distribution of the number of buildings in the group that will be damaged by<br>high tides this year, as shown in the table below.<br><br>n 0 1 2 3 4<br>Probability that<br>exactly n buildings<br>are damaged by high<br>tides<br>0.920 0.015 0.010 0.020 0.035<br><br>Calculate the probability that at least one of these buildings is damaged by high tides this<br>year given that at least one of these buildings is undamaged by high tides this year.<br><br>A) 0.0466<br>B) 0.0800<br>C) 0.0829<br>D) 0.5625<br>E) 0.7500", "tags": ["ExamP::GeneralProbability", "ExamP::GeneralProbability::ConditionalProbability"]},
    {"back": "<b>Answer: E) 57/400</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>At least eight problems are resolved if and only if the two technicians achieve one of the<br>following joint records of problem resolution:<br><br>Problems Solved by Problems Solved by Probability<br>Technician #1 Technician #2<br><br>5 5 (2/20)(2/20) = 4/400<br>5 4 (2/20)(3/20) = 6/400<br>4 5 (3/20)(2/20) = 6/400<br>4 4 (3/20)(3/20) = 9/400<br>5 3 (2/20)(8/20) = 16/400<br>3 5 (8/20)(2/20) = 16/400<br><br>The solution is the sum, 57/400.<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q662. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "The manager of a customer service team finds that the number of technical problems a<br>technician resolves in an hour follows the distribution below:<br>Number of<br>Technical<br>Problems<br>Resolved in an<br>Hour<br>0 1 2 3 4 5<br>Probability 1/20 2/20 4/20 8/20 3/20 2/20<br>The number of technical problems resolved in an hour by any particular technician is<br>independent of the number resolved in that hour by any other technician.<br><br>Calculate the probability that two technicians will resolve at least eight technical problems in an<br>hour.<br><br>A) 25/400<br>B) 35/400<br>C) 41/400<br>D) 48/400<br>E) 57/400", "tags": ["ExamP::GeneralProbability", "ExamP::GeneralProbability::Independence"]},
    {"back": "<b>Answer: B) 0.26</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>Let X denote the time it takes to complete the 5 reports. We want:<br>[ ]<br>[ ]<br>P[7.5 8]P[ 8| 7.5] P 7.5<br>7.5 7.5 8 7.5P P 0 0.3331.5 1.5<br>7.5 7.5 P[ 0]P 1.5<br>0.13056 0.2611.0.5<br>XXX X<br>Z Z<br>ZZ<br>\u2264\u2264\u2264 \u2265= \u2265<br>\u2212\u2212\uf8ee\uf8f9 \u2264\u2264\uf8ef\uf8fa \u2264\u2264\uf8f0\uf8fb= =\u2212 \u2265\uf8ee\uf8f9 \u2265\uf8ef\uf8fa\uf8f0\uf8fb<br>= =<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q663. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "Each day, an insurance claims adjuster is assigned five reports to complete. The total<br>time required to complete all five reports is normally distributed with mean 7.5 hours and<br>standard deviation 1.5 hours.<br><br>Calculate the probability that the claims adjuster will be finished in eight hours or less<br>given that he is still working after seven and one-half hours.<br><br>A) 0.13<br>B) 0.26<br>C) 0.37<br>D) 0.63<br>E) 0.74", "tags": ["ExamP::UnivariateRV", "ExamP::UnivariateRV::ContinuousDistributions"]},
    {"back": "<b>Answer: B) 10<br>9 10<br>e<br>e\u2212</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>1 20,000 120,000 1P[ 20000] .X ee e<br>\u2212<br>\u2212&gt;= = = The answer is binomial for number of losses:<br><br>9 10<br>10 10<br>10 101 1 1 10( 1) 1 10 91.9 10<br>ee<br>ee e e e<br>\uf8eb\uf8f6 \uf8eb\uf8f6 \u2212+ \u2212\uf8eb\uf8f6 \uf8eb \uf8f6 \uf8eb\uf8f6\u2212+ = =\uf8ec\uf8f7 \uf8ec\uf8f7\uf8ec\uf8f7 \uf8ec \uf8f7 \uf8ec\uf8f7\uf8ed\uf8f8 \uf8ed \uf8f8 \uf8ed\uf8f8\uf8ed\uf8f8 \uf8ed\uf8f8<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q664. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "The amount of losses for barn fires is exponentially distributed with mean 20,000.<br><br>Determine the probability that at least nine of a random sample of ten barn fires will have<br>losses in excess of 20,000.<br><br>A) 10<br>10 9<br>e<br>e\u2212<br>B) 10<br>9 10<br>e<br>e\u2212<br>C) 10<br>9)11 )( 9 (<br>e<br>ee \u2212 +<br>D) \uf8f7<br>\uf8f8<br>\uf8f6\uf8ec<br>\uf8ed<br>\uf8eb \u2212<br>10<br>110 e<br>e<br>E) 10<br>19 \uf8f7<br>\uf8f8<br>\uf8f6\uf8ec<br>\uf8ed<br>\uf8eb \u2212<br>e<br>e", "tags": ["ExamP::UnivariateRV", "ExamP::UnivariateRV::ContinuousDistributions"]},
    {"back": "<b>Answer: C) 0.97</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>The mean for a 100 page document is 100(0.10) = 10.<br>10 0 10 1 10 2 10 3 10 4<br>P[ 4] 1 P[ 4] 1 (P[ 0] P[ 1] P[ 2] P[ 3] P[ 4]<br>10 10 10 10 101 0! 1! 2! 3! 4!<br>1 (.000045 .00045 .00227 .00757 .01892) 0.97075.<br>X X X XX X X<br>eeeee\u2212\u2212\u2212\u2212\u2212<br>&gt; = \u2212\u2264 = \u2212 = += += += +=<br>= \u2212\u2212\u2212\u2212\u2212<br>= \u2212 ++++ =<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q665. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "The number of errors on any page of text produced at a particular office is modeled by a<br>Poisson distribution with mean 0.10. The number of errors on any one page is<br>independent of the number of errors on all other pages.<br><br>Calculate the probability of more than four errors in a 100-page document produced at<br>the office.<br><br>A) 0.01<br>B) 0.03<br>C) 0.97<br>D) 0.98<br>E) 0.99", "tags": ["ExamP::UnivariateRV", "ExamP::UnivariateRV::DiscreteDistributions"]},
    {"back": "<b>Answer: B) 0.39</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>P[10.5 11.5] 0.80X&lt;&lt; =<br>By symmetry of the normal distribution:<br>P[ 11.5] 0.90<br>11.5 11P Z&lt; 0.90<br>11.5 11 1.28155<br>0.39015.<br>X<br>\u03c3<br>\u03c3<br>\u03c3<br>&lt;=<br>\u2212\uf8ee\uf8f9 =\uf8ef\uf8fa\uf8f0\uf8fb<br>\u2212 =<br>=<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q666. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "Engineering specifications require that the probability a ball bearing produced at a<br>manufacturing plant has diameter between 10.5 and 11.5 is at least 0,8. The diameters of<br>these ball bearings are normally distributed with mean 11 and standard deviation \u03c3.<br><br>Calculate the largest value of \u03c3 for which the specification is met.<br><br>A) 0.15<br>B) 0.39<br>C) 0.59<br>D) 1.60<br>E) 2.56", "tags": ["ExamP::UnivariateRV", "ExamP::UnivariateRV::ContinuousDistributions"]},
    {"back": "<b>Answer: C) 381,000</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>For the exponential model, the 80<br>th percentile is 5001 0.8, 804.7190<br>p<br>ep<br>\u2212<br>\u2212= = .<br>For the normal distribution, the z-value of the 80th percentile is 0.84162. Hence,<br>804.7190 500 0.84162, 362.06245.\u03c3\u03c3<br>\u2212 = = . Then the second moment is<br>2 22E( ) 362.06245 500 381,089.X = +=<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q667. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "Actuary Tong models claim size from a random sample using a normal distribution with<br>mean 500. Actuary Bob models claim size from the same sample using an exponential<br>distribution with mean 500.<br><br>The 80<br>th percentiles for the two distributions are the same.<br><br>Calculate the second moment, to the nearest thousand, of the claim size according to<br>Tong\u2019s model.<br><br>A) 131,000<br>B) 145,000<br>C) 381,000<br>D) 395,000<br>E) 500,000", "tags": ["ExamP::UnivariateRV", "ExamP::UnivariateRV::ContinuousDistributions"]},
    {"back": "<b>Answer: E) 63</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>Let the interval be from a to b. The median is 6 = (a + b)/2 leading to the equation a + b = 12.<br>The 90<br>th percentile is 13.2 =0.1a +-0.9b leading to the equation a +9b = 132. Subtracting the<br>first equation from the second yields 8b = 120 for b = 15 and then a = \u20133. The second moment is<br><br>15 1523<br>33<br>(1/18) / 54 (3375 27) / 54 63.x dx x<br>\u2212\u2212<br>= = +=\u222b<br>Alternatively, using the formulas for the variance and mean of the uniform distribution the<br>second moment is 22[15 ( 3)] /12 [(15 ( 3))/2] 27 36 63.\u2212\u2212 + +\u2212 = + =<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q668. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "The random variable X is uniformly distributed on an interval and has median 6 and 90<br>th<br>percentile 13.20.<br><br>Calculate the second moment of X.<br><br>A) 6<br>B) 27<br>C) 33<br>D) 36<br>E) 63", "tags": ["ExamP::UnivariateRV", "ExamP::UnivariateRV::ContinuousDistributions"]},
    {"back": "<b>Answer: C) 119</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>Let p = probability of nonnegative annual profit in a given year.<br><br>Then 0.36 = P[negative annual profit in at least one of the next two years] = 1 \u2013 p<br>2.<br>So, p = 0.80.<br><br>Since the mean is 100, then by symmetry the probability that a given annual profit is less than<br>200 is also 0.80.<br><br>From the normal table, a cumulative probability 0.80 yields an approximate z-score of 0.84162.<br>So annual profits of 100 and 200 correspond to z-scores of 0 and approximately 0.84162,<br>respectively.<br><br>This means that a profit difference of 200 \u2013 100 = 100 represents approximately 0.84162 \u2013 0 =<br>0.84162 standard deviations. Thus the standard deviation of the annual profit is<br>100 118.82.0.84162 =<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q669. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "A boat insurance company\u2019s annual profit is normally distributed with mean 100. The<br>mean and standard deviation remain constant from year to year, and the annual profits are<br>independent.<br><br>The probability that the company\u2019s annual profit is negative in at least one of the next two<br>years is 0.36.<br><br>Calculate the standard deviation of the insurance company\u2019s annual profit.<br><br>A) 84<br>B) 109<br>C) 119<br>D) 125<br>E) 127", "tags": ["ExamP::GeneralProbability", "ExamP::GeneralProbability::Independence"]},
    {"back": "<b>Answer: A) 822</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>The 95<br>th percentile of the loss is 2500+1.6449(500) = 3322.45. Since the median and the mean<br>are the same, the median is 2500. Therefore, the excess is 3322.45 \u2013 2500 = 822.45.<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q670. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "The loss on an automobile policy is normally distributed with mean 2500 and standard<br>deviation 500.<br><br>The premium P for the policy is set such that the probability that a loss exceeds P is 5%.<br><br>Calculate the amount by which P exceeds the median loss.<br><br>A) 822<br>B) 980<br>C) 2500<br>D) 3322<br>E) 3480", "tags": ["ExamP::UnivariateRV", "ExamP::UnivariateRV::ContinuousDistributions"]},
    {"back": "<b>Answer: C) 0.341</b><br><br><b>Published solution:</b><br>The mean of the sum is<br>70 80 150.+= The standard deviation of the sum is<br>0.52214 20 24.4131.\uf8ee\uf8f9 +=\uf8f0\uf8fb The mean of the average is 150 75.2 = The standard deviation is<br>24.4131 12.2066.2 = The z-score we are looking for is 80 75 0.4096.12.2066<br>\u2212 = So, we want<br>[ ][ 80] 0.4096 0.34105.PX PZ&gt;= &gt; =<br><br><span style=\"color:#888;font-size:12px\">SOA Exam P Sample Questions/Solutions, Q671. https://www.soa.org/globalassets/assets/files/edu/edu-exam-p-sample-quest.pdf</span>", "front": "Two individuals were born today. The age at death of the first is normally distributed<br>with mean 70 and standard deviation 14. The age at death of the second is normally<br>distributed with mean 80 and standard deviation 20. The ages at death are independent.<br><br>Calculate the probability that the average age at death of the two individuals exceeds 80.<br><br>A) 0.119<br>B) 0.238<br>C) 0.341<br>D) 0.381<br>E) 0.659", "tags": ["ExamP::UnivariateRV", "ExamP::UnivariateRV::ContinuousDistributions"]},
